Roman\";=0A\tmso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;}=0A</style><p><![endif]-->=\n=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>Benefits for Genealogical Researchers</strong></p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\tGiving the NYG&amp;B's research collection to the NYPL benefited the ge=\nnealogical community because the collection is now more easily and widely a=\nvailable to the public, both at the NYPL's=C2=A0 <a href=3D\"../../libraryco=\nllection\">Research Library</a> (Stephen A. Schwarzman Building, Fifth Avenu=\ne and 42nd Street) and through the online catalog. An additional synergisti=\nc benefit is that the new home of the NYG&amp;B=E2=80=99s collection is one=\n of the great genealogical libraries in the United States. The library is p=\nrofessionally staffed, has expansive hours of operation, and includes acces=\ns to genealogical databases that are otherwise available only by subscripti=\non (e.g. Ancestry.com) or in libraries (e.g. ProQuest.) View an <a href=3D\"=\nhttp://www.nypl.org/locations/schwarzman/milstein-division-us-history-local=\n-history-genealogy\" target=3D\"_blank\">introduction to the NYPL's research r=\nesources for family history</a>.=C2=A0 For assistance to find items from th=\ne NYG&amp;B collection at the NYPL and for Catalog search tips, read our <a=\n href=3D\"/nyplsearch/\">guide</a>.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>A Shared Commitment =\nto Education</strong></p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe gift of the=C2=A0 NYG&amp;B's resear=\nch collections to the NYPL was the beginning of a symbiotic relationship. B=\noth the The New York Genealogical and Biographical Society and the New York=\n Public Library share fundamental values of advancing knowledge, reaching p=\neople of all backgrounds and ages, and building community through discoveri=\nng and sharing knowledge.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>Jointly Sponsored Programs</=\nstrong></p>=0A<p>=0A\tThroughout the year, the NYG&amp;B jointly sponsor pro=\ngrams which take place in the facilities of the Schwarzman Building. View a=\n <a href=3D\"../../nygbs-events\">list of NYG&amp;B programs</a>, which inclu=\nde the jointly sponsored offerings. These programs are free.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<=\nstrong>Reaching Special Audiences</strong></p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe NYPL and the NY=\nG&amp;B have teamed up to produce programs which teach teachers how to use =\ngenealogy in the classroom. The idea is to teach dozens of teachers who can=\n reach hundreds, possibly thousands, of students, some of whom will become =\nthe genealogists and family historians of the future. We have also collabor=\nated on a project involving The Tenement Museum.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>Reach=\ning Communities</strong></p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe fall of 2011 is the time we will =\npilot programs in selected branch libraries in Manhattan, the Bronx, and St=\naten Island. These programs will introduce branch library patrons to basic =\ngenealogical techniques, and more focused material related to ethnic popula=\ntions in New York, including Irish and African American communities.</p>=0A=\n<p class=3D\"MsoNormal\">=0A\t=C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =\n=0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </di=\nv>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/=\nprivacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms =\nof Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a=\n></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <=\nli><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=\n=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogic=\nal-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank=\n\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\"=\n alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http:/=\n/twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img sr=\nc=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Tw=\nitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr=\n.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/=\nall/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  b=\norder=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        N=\new York Genealogical &amp; <div id=3D\"main\" role=3D\"main\" class=3D\"clearfix\">=0A            <aside>=\n=0A                =0A                  <div id=3D\"secondary-menu\" class=3D=\n\"navigation\">=0A            <h2 class=3D\"element-invisible\">Secondary menu<=\n/h2><ul id=3D\"secondary-menu-links\" class=3D\"links clearfix\"><li class=3D\"m=\nenu-1187 first\"><a href=3D\"/about-nygb\" title=3D\"\">About the NYG&amp;B</a><=\n/li>=0A<li class=3D\"menu-1191 active-trail active\"><a href=3D\"/history-nygb=\ns\" title=3D\"\" class=3D\"active-trail active\">History of the NYG&amp;B</a></l=\ni>=0A<li class=3D\"menu-1192\"><a href=3D\"/nypl-partnership\" title=3D\"\">NYG&a=\nmp;B &amp; NYPL Partnership</a></li>=0A<li class=3D\"menu-1188\"><a href=3D\"/=\nLeadership\" title=3D\"\">NYG&amp;B Leadership</a></li>=0A<li class=3D\"menu-11=\n89\"><a href=3D\"/staff-list\" title=3D\"\">Staff</a></li>=0A<li class=3D\"menu-1=\n193\"><a href=3D\"/publication\" title=3D\"\">Publications</a></li>=0A<li class=\n=3D\"menu-1190 last\"><a href=3D\"/nygbs-faq\" title=3D\"\">FAQs</a></li>=0A</ul>=\n          </div> <!-- /#secondary-menu -->=0A                =0A           =\n     =0A      </aside>=0A            <article class=3D\"\">      =0A         =\n       =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A               =\n       History of the NYG&amp;B           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A             =\n     <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-ma=\nin\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A =\n   <div id=3D\"node-14\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/history-=\nnygbs\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"co=\nntent\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=\n=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/14\" title=3D\"Display a printer-fr=\niendly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(t=\nhis.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-ic=\non-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sit=\nes/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\"=\n title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></=\nspan><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field=\n-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" pr=\noperty=3D\"content:encoded\"><h2>=0A\t<a name=3D\"top\" id=3D\"top\"></a>The New Y=\nork Genealogical and Biographical Society is the oldest genealogical societ=\ny in New York State and the second oldest in the nation.=C2=A0</h2>=0A<h3>=\n=0A\tContents</h3>=0A<ul><li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"#founding\">Founding in 1869</a>=\n</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"#headquarters\">Headquarters Facilities</a></li>=\n=0A<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"#Publications\">Early Publications</a></li>=0A<li>=0A=\n\t\t<a href=3D\"#twentieth\">The NYG&amp;B in the Twentieth Century</a></li>=0A=\n<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"#renaissance\">Genealogical Renaissance</a></li>=0A<li>=\n=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"#New\">The New G&amp;B</a></li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"#A\">Ap=\npendix A: About Women in the Early Years of the NYG&amp;B</a></li>=0A<li>=\n=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"#B\">Appendix B: A Note About Elizabeth Underhill Coles</a><=\n/li>=0A</ul><h3>=0A\tFounding in 1869<a name=3D\"founding\" id=3D\"founding\"></=\na></h3>=0A<p>=0A\tSeven men meeting on the evening of February 27, 1869, at =\nthe home of Dr. David Parsons Holton in New York City, organized The New Yo=\nrk Genealogical and Biographical Society. On March 26 they filed a certific=\nate of incorporation in the office of the Secretary of State of New York, s=\ntating that \"the particular business and objects of the Society are to disc=\nover, procure, preserve and perpetuate whatever may relate to Genealogy and=\n Biography, and more particularly to the genealogies and biographies of fam=\nilies, persons and citizens associated and identified with the State of New=\n York.\" In April they adopted the first By-Laws and elected officers, the f=\nirst president being the historian Dr. Henry R. Stiles. The officers adopte=\nd the seal of the Society on May 8, 1869.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tIn establishing the =\nSociety the founders were inspired by the example of the New England Histor=\nic Genealogical Society, founded in 1845. In at least one respect, however,=\n they differed from the New England model. While women would not be admitte=\nd to membership in the Boston society until 1898, the New York society on M=\nay 1, 1869 elected to membership Frances K. Forward Holton, who was the wif=\ne of Dr. Holton. She was followed by many others.=C2=A0 More information on=\n Mrs. Holton appears in Appendix A below.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe Society immediat=\nely established a library, and in December 1869 published an eight-page <em=\n>Bulletin. </em>The reception of this publication encouraged the Trustees t=\no launch a quarterly journal, <em>The New York Genealogical and Biographica=\nl Record,</em> the first issue of which was dated January 1870. Thus were e=\nstablished two of the oldest institutions in American genealogy. Today the =\nSociety is the second oldest genealogical society in the United States, and=\n <em>The Record</em> the second-oldest genealogical periodical in continuou=\ns publication in the English-speaking world.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\">=\nRETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tHeadquarters Facilities<a name=3D\"headquart=\ners\" id=3D\"headquarters\"></a></h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe Society's first permanent h=\nome was at Mott Memorial Hall, a house at 64 Madison Avenue. In 1888 the So=\nciety obtained space in the Berkeley Lyceum Building at 19 West 41st Street=\n, and two years later moved to the new Berkeley Lyceum building at 23 West =\n44th Street, just a few steps away from where the NYG&amp;B is today.</p>=\n=0A<p>=0A\tIn 1891 Mrs. Elizabeth Underhill Coles died, leaving the Society =\na bequest of $20,000.=C2=A0 With this money the Society was able to purchas=\ne in 1896 a four-story brownstone at 226 West 58th Street, between Broadway=\n and Seventh Avenue. This became \"Genealogical Hall,\" the home of the Socie=\nty for the next 33 years.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tOne of the Society's most ambitious =\nearly projects was the placement of a statue of Christopher Columbus on the=\n Mall in New York's Central Park to mark the quadricentennial of Columbus=\n=E2=80=99s voyage to the New World in 1492. The bronze statue, a replica of=\n a work by Spanish sculptor Jeronimo Sunol (1849-1902), arrived in New York=\n on June 8, 1893. Adlai E. Stevenson, Vice-President of the United States, =\nunveiled the statue in 1894 on the spot where it stands today.</p>=0A<p>=0A=\n\tBy 1912 Genealogical Hall was inadequate to hold the library, and the Trus=\ntees decided to raise $65,000 to acquire the adjacent building lot for expa=\nnsion. J. Pierpont Morgan contributed $10,000 on the condition that the Soc=\niety raise the remainder, and this was accomplished by the end of 1913, mai=\nnly through the efforts of president Clarence Winthrop Bowen. Various facto=\nrs intervened to prevent the proposed expansion, and Mr. Bowen was still pr=\nesident 16 years later when the Society moved across town into its next loc=\nation at 122-124-126 East 58th Street.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe new facility, erect=\ned at a cost of $300,000, replaced three brownstone houses on the site. The=\n noted New York architectural firm of La Farge, Warren and Clark designed t=\nhe building. An impressive list of dignitaries, headed by former President =\nof the United States Calvin Coolidge and former Governor of New York and Se=\ncretary of State (and future Chief Justice of the United States) Charles Ev=\nans Hughes attended the formal dedication on December 11, 1929.</p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\tThe new building provided impressive and ample space for the growth of =\nthe library.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\t=\nEarly Publications<a name=3D\"Publications\" id=3D\"Publications\"></a></h3>=0A=\n<p>=0A\tOver the years the Society had also expanded its publications progra=\nm. By 1929 each issue of <em>The Record </em>ran over 100 pages, and it had=\n become recognized as one of the leading scholarly journals of genealogy. S=\nince 1890 the Society had also published several volumes of its collections=\n, starting with the marriage and baptismal registers of New York State's ol=\ndest church, the Reformed Dutch Church of New Amsterdam and New York City.<=\n/p>=0A<p>=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B=\n in the Twentieth Century<a name=3D\"twentieth\" id=3D\"twentieth\"></a></h3>=\n=0A<p>=0A\tThe Great Depression and World War II slowed the Society's progre=\nss =E2=80=94 <em>The Record,</em> for example, became greatly reduced in si=\nze. In this period, and the years after the war, interest in genealogy had =\ndeclined and some may have questioned whether the Society could survive.</p>=\n=0A<p>=0A\tBut amazing changes were in the offing.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tWhen the Soc=\niety was founded in 1869, the only New Yorkers who had an interest in traci=\nng their roots, or the time to do so, were those whose lineages stretched b=\nack to the colonial period, and the Society for its first hundred years cat=\nered almost exclusively to that part of the population. Even among those wi=\nth colonial ancestry, however, there were relatively few who had more than =\na passing interest in their family history. Genealogy remained a rather obs=\ncure hobby and its status as a profession was even more tenuous.</p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tGenealogical Renaissan=\nce<a name=3D\"renaissance\" id=3D\"renaissance\"></a></h3>=0A<p>=0A\tIn the 1970=\ns there were signs of change.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe 19th century was now more di=\nstant than the 18th had been in 1869, and there was increasing interest in =\nits records, which were also now becoming more accessible. Descendants of 1=\n9th century immigrants, and Americans of African descent, discovered that t=\nhey too could delve into genealogy. The telecast based on Alex Haley's book=\n <em>Roots </em>and the 1976 Bicentennial were catalysts that precipitated =\nthis new wave of interest.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe increased mobility of the popul=\nation, leaving so many Americans far removed from their roots, and an incre=\nase in leisure time, especially among older Americans, were other factors i=\nn the expansion.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tAll over the country new genealogical societi=\nes, publications, and activities developed, and the older institutions bega=\nn to experience unprecedented growth as well. The Society was similarly aff=\nected by this growth.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tIn the late 1980s computers began to be =\nused in administration, publishing, and the library. The library began to s=\nignificantly expand its microform holdings to facilitate research in late 1=\n9th century and early 20th century sources, while also expanding its coloni=\nal collection. In 1990, the NYG&amp;B launched <em>The NYG&amp;B Newsletter=\n;</em> in 2004 it became <em>The New York Researcher</em>. In 2003 the Soci=\nety began publication of all past issues of <em>The Record</em> on CD-ROM.=\n=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe Society's formal education programs began in 1977 w=\nith a fall lecture series. The educational program expanded in the 1990s to=\n include programs at such locations as Albany, Saratoga Springs, Buffalo, T=\narrytown, and Elizabeth, NJ, often in cooperation with other genealogical s=\nocieties. The Society began to establish a presence at national, regional a=\nnd local genealogical conferences sponsored by other organizations.</p>=0A<=\np>=0A\tIn the mid-1990s genealogy began to undergo a sea change with the adv=\nent of the internet. The number of Americans (and people in many other coun=\ntries) pursuing genealogy skyrocketed as a result. The Society joined this =\nnew world in December 1998 when it launched its own website.=C2=A0 Its Memb=\ners' Area included the NYG&amp;B eLibrary, a growing database of the Societ=\ny=E2=80=99s unique manuscript holdings.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=0A\tBy the lat=\ne 1990s the Society's record growth=C2=A0 motivated it to make changes in t=\nhe building and develop a master plan for its future. To implement the chan=\nges, the Society conducted a capital campaign drive for the first time in m=\nany decades. In 1999 it was possible to begin the first stage of the plan. =\nIn 2001 the NYG&amp;B created the Technology Center for microform and compu=\nter media. This served members for several years, but the internet continue=\nd to reduce member visits to the research library.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tMore and mo=\nre members spent less and less time at the library, preferring instead to m=\nake use of the online offerings from home. As a result foot traffic slowed =\ndown, and it was again time to reassess the mission of the Society and the =\nrole of its building and traditional library.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\"=\n>RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe New NYG&amp;B<a name=3D\"New\" id=3D\"New=\n\"></a></h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe board of trustees analyzed the state of the NYG&am=\np;B and studied the field of endeavor in which it operated. The board ultim=\nately decided that the business model, in place for decades, had become uns=\nustainable.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t=C2=A0As a consequence NYG&amp;B gave its library =\ncollections over to the New York Public Library, one of the largest and mos=\nt important research libraries in the world. Its genealogical and family hi=\nstory collections were already local, national, and international in scope =\nbut the addition of the NYG&amp;B collections added significant new depth a=\nnd breadth. The gift of books and manuscripts was accompanied by sufficient=\n funds to underwrite the cataloging of the collection.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tPart of=\n the transfer of the library included a formal agreement to work together t=\no advance genealogical and family history research and education in New Yor=\nk.=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=0A\tIn September, 2008 the published books moved sixteen =\nblocks south to the Public Library's Irma &amp; Paul Milstein Division of U=\nnited States History, Local History, and Genealogy, and the manuscripts wen=\nt to the Manuscripts Division of the NYPL.=C2=A0 The NYPL then set about ca=\ntaloging the books and manuscripts and adding them to the online catalog. T=\nhis resulted in a vastly broader awareness of the collections to the public=\n, since the catalog became available to anyone in the world with an interne=\nt connection, and the books and manuscripts became available not just to NY=\nG&amp;B members and guests, but to anyone at all who could get to the NYPL =\nresearch library.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B found a buyer for the building=\n on 58th Street in November, 2007. With the sale of that headquarters came =\nthe necessity of finding another. In November 2008 the Society purchased a =\ncommercial condominium at 36 West 44th Street in the landmark Bar Building =\nand created entirely new offices on the 7th floor. The well-known New York =\narchitect Peter Pennoyer and designer John Claflin are responsible for the =\ndesign of the new NYG&amp;B offices.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B furnished t=\nhe new space with items from the 58th Street building, including two of the=\n splendid walnut library tables and all of the walnut chairs, together with=\n selections from the NYG&amp;B portrait collection. The staff completed the=\n move in January of 2010.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B=E2=80=99s move to West=\n 44th Street was more than just a physical relocation.=C2=A0 Accompanying i=\nt was a change in leadership and a significant realignment of strategic dir=\nection and purpose.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tWithout the burden of maintaining a large =\nbuilding and library, the NYG&amp;B refocused itself on three priorities: e=\nducation, publications, and digital communication.</p>=0A<ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t=\n\t\t<strong>Education</strong><strong>.</strong> the staff significantly incr=\neased the volume of public programs and began the process of integrating th=\ne programs of other important, like-minded institutions under the umbrella =\nof The New York Family History School. Early partner organizations in devel=\noping this idea included the New York Public Library and the National Archi=\nves and Records Administration in Manhattan. The NYG&amp;B created a websit=\ne for the New York Family History School and began to promote its own progr=\nams and those of the participating organizations.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=\n=0A\t\t\t<strong>Publications. </strong><em>The Record </em>continued publicat=\nion without interruption or change in its purpose and scholarly standards. =\n<em>The New York Researche</em>r, however, underwent a total redesign and b=\negan its evolution to being more of a magazine rather than an NYG&amp;B new=\nsletter.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Digital communication</stron=\ng><strong>.</strong> The NYG&amp;B improved its capability to implement dig=\nital media solutions, began participating in social media marketing, and cr=\neated this new website.=C2=A0 Increasing the size and functionality of the =\neLibrary became a priority and a team of unusually capable volunteers conti=\nnue to lead that effort.</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><p>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B moves forw=\nard today into the 21st century as an educational institution committed to =\nhelping people of all backgrounds connect with their families and their com=\nmunities and to find their connections with the people, places, and events =\npivotal in American history.=C2=A0 Achieving those benefits is more possibl=\ne than ever today with improved training in research, analytical, and writi=\nng skills and access to ever increasing volumes of quality data.</p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tAppendix A: Note About=\n Women in the Early Years of the NYG&amp;B<a name=3D\"A\" id=3D\"A\"></a></h3>=\n=0A<p>=0A\tMembers of NYG&amp;BS may be interested to know that women were w=\nelcome as members of our Society from the time of its founding in 1869.=C2=\n=A0 The first woman member was Frances K. Forward Holton (Mrs. David P.), w=\nho was elected to membership on May 1, 1869. She was followed over the next=\n twenty-five years by:</p>=0A<p>=0A\tMiss Elizabeth Clarkson Jay<br />=0A\tMr=\ns. Leroy Newcomb Shear<br />=0A\tMiss Annie Elizabeth Boutecon Shepard<br />=\n=0A\tCaroline Gallup Reed (Mrs. Sylvanus)<br />=0A\tMartha Joanna Reade Nash =\nLamb (Mrs. Charles A.)<br />=0A\tMartha Bayard Dodd Stevens (Mrs. Edwin A.)<=\nbr />=0A\tMargaret Herbert Mather (Mrs. DeWitt C.)<br />=0A\tKatharine Newton=\n Youmans (Mrs. Edward L.)<br />=0A\tEmilie Ketchum Platt Owen (Mrs. Thomas J=\n.)<br />=0A\tMary Macrae Stuart (Mrs. Robert L.)<br />=0A\tJanet Van Renssela=\ner Townsend (Mrs. Howard)<br />=0A\tAurelia Davis Schoonmaker (Mrs. Lucas E.=\n)<br />=0A\tCatharine Romana Marsiglia Baetjer (Mrs. Herman)<br />=0A\tEster =\nVan Ysen Herrman (Mrs. Henry)<br />=0A\tEba Anderson Lawton (Mrs. James M.)<=\nbr />=0A\tMiss Ann Hasbrouck<br />=0A\tMary Ann Hart (Mrs. Coleridge)<br />=\n=0A\tMiss Carrie Allen Middlebrook<br />=0A\tKatharine Berry di Zerega (Mrs. =\nJohn A.)<br />=0A\tLilly Jones Earle (Mrs. Ferdinand P.)<br />=0A\tMiss Bessi=\ne Thayer Sypher (later Mrs. Charles C. Marsh)<br />=0A\tMiss Margaret Morris=\n Norwood<br />=0A\tElizabeth Ward Doremus (Mrs. Charles A.)<br />=0A\tMiss Ma=\nry Mildred Williams<br />=0A\tGeorgie Harrington Boyden St. John (Mrs. Gamal=\niel C.)<br />=0A\tEllen Hardin Walworth (Mrs. Mansfield T.)<br />=0A\tMiss Lu=\ncy Dubois Akerly<br />=0A\tMrs. Mary Wright Wootton<br />=0A\tMargaret Innis =\nYoung (Mrs. William H.)<br />=0A\tMrs. Cornelia Catharine Jay Dyer<br />=0A\t=\nMiss Mary Close Purple<br />=0A\tElizabeth Romaine McMillan-Stanton (Mrs. Jo=\nhn)<br />=0A\tMiss Reba Bird Whitfield</p>=0A<p>=0A\tAfter 1894 there was a n=\noticeable increase in the number of women on the lists of new members. Toda=\ny, of course, women make up at least half of the membership of the Society.=\n</p>=0A<p>=0A\tIt should surprise no one that women were not given positions=\n of responsibility during the Society=E2=80=99s early years. At the twenty-=\nfifth anniversary in 1894 twenty-two women members (all named above) did fo=\nrm the committee for an afternoon reception, but some years would pass befo=\nre women began to serve on special committees and in other responsible capa=\ncities.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tIt was 1941 when Bertha King Benkard (Mrs. Harry Horto=\nn Benkard) became the first woman Trustee, followed in 1943 by Mrs. Myron C=\n. Taylor and Mrs. John M. Dickinson, in 1945 by Mrs. Ethelbert Ide Low, and=\n in 1946 by Mrs. Wyllys Terry. Since then the Board has always had women me=\nmbers, and women have served as officers as well. In 1983 Mrs. William R. W=\nhite became the Society=E2=80=99s first woman President.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tWomen=\n have served the Society in many staff positions, including Executive Direc=\ntor (formerly Executive Secretary) and Director of the Library (formerly As=\nsociate Librarian). The roll of honors given by the Society contains the na=\nmes of many women, among them outstanding genealogists who have been made F=\nellows or Corresponding Members.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tA long list of women have wri=\ntten articles for<em> The NYG&amp;B Record </em>and <em>The New York Resear=\ncher. </em>Many others have volunteered their time, especially in the Libra=\nry. And last but by no means least, some of the most generous donors to the=\n Society have been women, beginning in 1891 with Mrs. Elizabeth Underhill C=\noles whose bequest permitted the purchase of our first permanent home.</p>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tAppendix B: A No=\nte About Elizabeth Underhill Coles<a name=3D\"B\" id=3D\"B\"></a></h3>=0A<p>=0A=\n\tElizabeth Underhill Coles=E2=80=99 bequest of $20,000 made it possible for=\n the Society to purchase in 1896 the building at 226 West 58th Street which=\n was our home (called Genealogical Hall) until the the Society moved to Eas=\nt 58th Street in 1929.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tGenealogists familiar with early Long I=\nsland family names will immediately suspect that Elizabeth Underhill Coles=\n=E2=80=99 roots may have been in Oyster Bay. She was indeed born in that to=\nwn, in the section known as Musketa Cove (now the City of Glen Cove). She w=\nas descended from a long list of early Long Island families, and many of he=\nr distant cousins are undoubtedly present day NYG&amp;BS members.=C2=A0</p>=\n=0A<p>\tElizabeth Underhill Coles, who was born ca.1813, kept her name by ma=\nrrying a first cousin, William F. Coles, in 1833. Her parents were Oliver a=\nnd Margaret (Underhill) Coles, and her grandparents were Gen. Nathaniel and=\n Hannah (Butler) Coles and Amos and Mary (Woodhull) Underhill. Her great-gr=\nandparents were Wright and Sarah (Birdsall) Coles, John and Martha (=E2=80=\n=94) Butler, Amos and Elizabeth (Seaman) Underhill, and Richard and Margare=\nt (Smith) Woodhull. Further details may be found beginning in the Underhill=\n Genealogy (1932) 3:557.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tMrs. Coles=E2=80=99 father, and her f=\nather-in-law John Butler Coles, were both prominent New York City merchants=\n, who created fortunes that made it possible for her and her husband to lea=\nd very comfortable lives. William F. Coles died in 1865. Their only son, Wi=\nlliam Franklin Coles, was one of the first members of The NYG&amp;B Society=\n. Elected to membership October 30, 1869, he became a Life Member in 1871, =\nand died unmarried in 1881, at age 43.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tElizabeth Underhill Col=\nes died December 29, 1891, at her residence, 677 Fifth Avenue, and was buri=\ned in the Coles vault at Trinity Church. She left an estate valued at betwe=\nen two and three million dollars. In her will written June 4, 1885, in addi=\ntion to the bequest to the NYG&amp;BS she gave a like amount to the Metropo=\nlitan Museum, along with a collection of paintings, sculpture and other wor=\nks of art. She left her property at Newport to establish =E2=80=9CColes Col=\nlege=E2=80=9D in memory of her son. The remainder of the estate was to be d=\nivided, half to go to the Cathedral of St. John the Divine in memory of her=\n husband, and from the other half, $50,000 to the children of her brother E=\ndward Coles, $100,000 in trust for Coles College, and the rest to her broth=\ner Alexander Coles and his family.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tEdward Coles, who had been =\nexecutor of the estate of Mrs. Coles=E2=80=99 husband, had expected to be t=\nreated more generously by his sister, and tried to have her will invalidate=\nd on the grounds that she was not of sound mind at the time she made it. At=\n a hearing in the New York County Surrogate=E2=80=99s Court he persuaded so=\nme of Mrs. Coles=E2=80=99 servants and his own wife to give testimony in su=\npport of his case, and the matter achieved some notoriety in the press. The=\n Surrogate, however, was not impressed; he ruled that the will was valid an=\nd admitted it to probate. (For further details see <em>The New York Times</=\nem>, Oct. 27-Nov. 4, 1892.)</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<em>The NYG&amp;B Record</em> of A=\npril 1892 (23:95) had reported Mrs. Coles=E2=80=99 death, noting that =E2=\n=80=9Cby her will Mrs. Coles left a legacy of twenty thousand dollars to th=\nis Society. If the intentions of our generous benefactor are not frustrated=\n, by relatives who are endeavoring to break her will, it is believed that t=\nhe Society will soon be in the possession of a firepoof building where our =\nvaluable collections will be safe from possible destruction by fire.=E2=80=\n=9D In the April 1894 issue (25:95) Henry R. Stiles noted in an obituary of=\n Charles B. Moore that =E2=80=9Chis last work of love to us seems to have b=\neen the securing for our Society the valuable bequest received from the lat=\ne Mrs. Coles. His influence, so unobtrusively yet effectually exercised in =\nthis matter . . . must ever be a pleasant remembrance to us. . . .=E2=80=9D=\n</p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe New York Genealogical and Biographical Society received t=\nhe bequest which provided it with Genealogical Hall, its first permanent ho=\nme. In 1898 Mrs. Coles was made a =E2=80=9Cperpetual member=E2=80=9D of the=\n Society. The sale of Genealogical Hall in 1929 helped to finance the Socie=\nty=E2=80=99s next home on East 58th Street. And the proceeds from the sale =\nof that building helps to finance the current operations of the NYG&amp;B. =\nAnd so Mrs. Coles=E2=80=99 legacy lives on.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<a href=3D\"#top\">R=\nETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A =\n </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=\n=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy<=\n/a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of Service</a></l=\ni>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a></li>=0A        =\n  <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"htt=\np://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a hre=\nf=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogical-Biographical-S=\nociety/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/si=\ntes/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook =\npage\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/n=\nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/t=\nhemes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  bord=\ner=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs=\n/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/=\nimages/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=\n=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        New York Genealogic=\nal &amp; Researcher, </em>a colorful magazine of news and i=\nnformation. Subscriptions are benefits of membership, and the full run of b=\noth is online for members. The NYG&amp;B also publishes items in other medi=\na.</h2>=0A<h3>=0A\t<em>The New York Genealogical and Biographical Record</em=\n></h3>=0A<p>=0A\t<em>The New York Genealogical and Biographical Record</em> =\nhas been published quarterly since 1870. With its long history of scholarly=\n publication,<em> The</em> <em>Record</em> is an essential New York source =\nfor genealogists, historians, and biographers.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<a class=3D\"btn=\n-link2\" href=3D\"/nygbr\">Learn More</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\t<em>The New York Resea=\nrcher</em></h3>=0A<p>=0A\t<em>The New York Researcher</em> is a colorful qua=\nrterly magazine that comes as a benefit of membership in the NYG&amp;B.=C2=\n=A0 Covered subjects include informative articles on New York genealogy, ne=\nws, book reviews, announcements, queries submitted by members, and the prog=\nrams of the New York Family History School.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<a class=3D\"btn-li=\nnk2\" href=3D\"/research\">Learn More</a></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe Monthly eNews</h3>=\n=0A<p>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B distributes a monthly newsletter electronically tha=\nt announces upcoming special programs sponsored by the NYG&amp;B or listed =\nin the calendar of the New York Family History School. Subscriptions are fr=\nee. You may sign up for a subscription on the homepage of this website by s=\nubmitting your email address. The NYG&amp;B never shares, rents, or otherwi=\nse discloses your email address to anyone at anytime.       =\n         <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-syste=\nm-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=\n=0A    <div id=3D\"node-6\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/nygbr=\n\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content=\n\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"h=\nttp://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/6\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly=\n version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.hr=\nef); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-mar=\ngin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all=\n/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=\n=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><=\ndiv class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label=\n-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=\n=3D\"content:encoded\"><h2><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content=\n-img/nygb-record.jpg\" alt=3D\"NYGBS Record\" style=3D\"float: left;\" class=3D\"=\nimg-float-right\" /></h2>=0A<h2><a name=3D\"top\" id=3D\"top\"></a></h2>=0A<h2>T=\nwenty-first century genealogists have research tools and opportunities that=\n their nineteenth-century counterparts would find astonishing. Yet <em>The =\nRecord</em>, published continuously since 1870, remains a constant in this =\nchanging world.</h2>=0A<p>The second-oldest genealogical journal in the Uni=\nted States, <em>The Record</em> has as its goal the scholarly preservation =\nof the history of families who have contributed to the rich diversity of wh=\nat is now New York State. Here you will find accounts of New York documente=\nd at the level of the individual and find that history is not only shaped b=\ny its prominent citizens, but by all of its residents, rich and poor alike.=\n</p>=0A<h3>The Mission of The Record</h3>=0A<p><strong>Adhering to scholarl=\ny standards, <em>The New York Genealogical and Biographical Record </em>pub=\nlishes written works that solve genealogical problems, provide compiled gen=\nealogies, make available transcriptions of original records, and offer rese=\narch guidance relevant to families who have contributed to the rich diversi=\nty of what is now New York State.</strong></p>=0A<p id=3D\"about\"><a name=3D=\n\"about the record\" id=3D\"about the record\"></a>With its long history of sch=\nolarly publication, <em>The Record</em> is an essential New York source for=\n genealogists, historians, and biographers, as well as individuals research=\ning their New York families. It is published four times a year, in January,=\n April, July, and October, and is a benefit of membership in the NYG&amp;B;=\n subscriptions to <em>The Record</em> are also available. NYG&amp;B members=\n also have online access to the complete run of<em> The Record</em>.</p>=0A=\n<p>Every issue of <em>The Record</em> contains articles that preserve the h=\nistory of the families and individuals who settled in New York. Those artic=\nles can include</p>=0A<ul><li>=0A<p>solutions to difficult problems, such a=\ns identifying a spouse, parents, or another place of residence, with the as=\nsociated genealogical summary;</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>compiled genealogies=\n of families beginning with an immigrant (in any time period) and covering =\nthe initial generations in America;</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>compiled geneal=\nogies beginning with a later American generation, especially those that ill=\nustrate use of unusual sources;</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>documentation of th=\ne origins of New York families in foreign countries or other colonies or st=\nates, with the associated genealogical summary;</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>cor=\nrections or additions to a prior article in <em>The Record</em>;</p>=0A</li>=\n=0A<li>=0A<p>transcriptions or abstracts of genealogically and/or historica=\nlly relevant records.</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><p><em>The NYG&amp;B Record</em> i=\ns one of a handful of highly respected peer-reviewed genealogical publicati=\nons in the country. Serious genealogists study its pages to learn about fam=\nilies, sources, history, and genealogical problem-solving techniques. Wheth=\ner or not the subject of an article is of direct interest in one=E2=80=99s =\nown research, readers can improve their own genealogical knowledge and skil=\nls by studying its contents.</p>=0A<h3>Thinking of Writing for <em>The Reco=\nrd</em>?</h3>=0A<p>Writing for a peer-reviewed publication such as <em>The =\nRecord</em> is a learning experience valued by many researchers, since thei=\nr submissions will receive input from experts in the field. Not every artic=\nle is accepted for publication, of course, but even those that are turned d=\nown are returned with suggestions for improvement. Authors who write for pu=\nblications like <em>The Record</em> are eager to have their work critiqued =\nand improved by their peers. Those articles accepted for publication will u=\nndergo several rounds of editing and vetting.</p>=0A<p>If you believe you m=\night be ready to submit a manuscript for consideration, study recent issues=\n of <em>The Record</em> to become familiar with the articles or pieces gene=\nrally published. Submissions should focus on residents of New York State an=\nd its colonial predecessors, or can deal with adjacent areas or countries o=\nf origin if there is significant migration to or from New York State. We se=\nek unique manuscripts=E2=80=94studying families of any ethnic, religious, o=\nr social group in any time period=E2=80=94that have not been published or s=\nubmitted for publication elsewhere.</p>=0A<h3>Additional Information</h3>=\n=0A<ul><li>=0A<p><a href=3D\"/writingfortherecord\">Guidelines for Submission=\ns to <em>The Record</em></a></p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p><a href=3D\"/advertisin=\ng\">Advertise in <em>The Record</em></a></p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p><a href=3D\"=\n/recordfundnonmbr\">Guide to the Fundamentals of Using <em>The Record </em>O=\nnline</a></p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p><a href=3D\"/worden-search\">Search Worden'=\ns Index of Family and Given Names in <em>The Record</em></a></p>=0A</li>=0A=\n<li>=0A<p><a href=3D\"/editors\">About the Co-Editors</a></p>=0A</li>=0A</ul>=\n</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </=\ndiv>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A </aside>=0A  =\n          <article class=3D\"\">      =0A                =0A         <h1 clas=\ns=3D\"title\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      The New York Researc=\nher           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region re=\ngion-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-sys=\ntem\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-7\" class=\n=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/research\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=\n=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"pri=\nnt-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.=\norg/print/7\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of this page.\" cla=\nss=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return false\" rel=3D\"n=\nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" =\nsrc=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons/print_=\nicon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly versio=\nn\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-na=\nme-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"fiel=\nd-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><p cla=\nss=3D\"rtecenter\">=0A\t<img alt=3D\"\" src=3D\"/sites/default/files/images/5(1).=\npng\" style=3D\"width: 616px; height: 257px;\" /></p>=0A<h2>=0A\t<em>The New Yo=\nrk Researcher </em>is a colorful quarterly that is a benefit of membership =\nin the NYG&amp;B.=C2=A0 Covered subjects include informative articles on Ne=\nw York genealogy, news, book reviews, announcements, queries submitted by m=\nembers, and the programs of the New York Family History School.</h2>=0A<h3 =\nalign=3D\"left\">=0A\tReading <em>The New York Researcher</em></h3>=0A<p align=\n=3D\"left\">=0A\tA searchable, complete run of <em>The New York Researcher</em=\n> and its predecessor publication the <em>NYG&amp;B Newslette</em>r, which =\nwas first published in 1990, is available in the eLibrary of this website t=\no NYG&amp;B members.</p>=0A<h3 align=3D\"left\">=0A\tFeature Articles</h3>=0A<=\np align=3D\"left\">=0A\tThe feature articles of <em>The New York </em><i>Resea=\nrcher</i> have made it a particularly useful research tool for New York gen=\nealogists. These articles cover topics such as</p>=0A<ul><li>=0A\t\tDescripti=\nons of sources for New York genealogy, such as probate, church, and census =\nrecords.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tDescriptions of holdings of other New York State l=\nibraries and record repositories.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t\"How to\" articles on New =\nYork genealogical research, both statewide and for particular counties or c=\nities, religious or ethnic groups, or time periods.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tLists o=\nf accounts of New York families \"hidden\" in multi-family works, manuscript =\ncollections, and periodicals.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tArticles on New York families=\n published in other periodicals, past and present</li>=0A</ul><h3>=0A\tGenea=\nlogical Exchange in <em>The New York Researcher</em></h3>=0A<p>=0A\tNYG&amp;=\nB members may submit a genealogical query not exceeding 100 words to each i=\nssue of <em>The New York Researcher</em>; queries submitted for printing in=\n <em>The New York Researcher</em> are also automatically posted online. (No=\nte also that you may post queries online yourself, independently of the pri=\nnted version. Click here to post online.) For queries to be printed in the =\nmagazine, send an email to <a href=3D\"mailto:education@nygbs.org\">education=\n@nygbs.org</a> or mail to the NYG&amp;B offices: 36 West 44th Street, New Y=\nork, NY 10036.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tSubmitting Material to <em>The New York Resear=\ncher</em></h3>=0A<p>=0A\tIf you have a story idea for <em>The New York Resea=\nrcher</em>, or would like to write an article, note, or book review, or hav=\ne a book to submit for a book review in <em>The New York Researcher</em>, p=\nlease <a href=3D\"mailto:education@nygbs.org\">contact the editor</a>.</p>=0A=\n<p>=0A\t=C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </=\ndiv>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A =\n     <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a><=\n/li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=\n=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          =\n<li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http:=\n//www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=\n=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogical-Biographical-So=\nciety/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sit=\nes/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook p=\nage\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/ny=\nfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/th=\nemes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  borde=\nr=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/=\n\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/i=\nmages/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=\n=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        New York Genealogic=\nal &amp; <!-- /#secondary-menu -->=0A  =\n              =0A                =0A      </aside>=0A            <article c=\nlass=3D\"\">      =0A                =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=3D\"pa=\nge-title\">=0A                      Research Tools for NYG&amp;B Members    =\n       \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region region-co=\nntent\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=\n=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-65\" class=3D\"n=\node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/public-researchtool\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Docum=\nent\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=\n=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyh=\nistory.org/print/65\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of this pa=\nge.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return false\" =\nrel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf=\n:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icon=\ns/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendl=\ny version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field =\nfield-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=\n=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded=\n\"><h2>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B provides many articles and original guides for memb=\ners to assist them in their research, including the most popular \"Research =\nAid\" articles that have been updated by experts in the field. Below is a li=\nst of resources available to members who log in, followed by some useful gu=\nides which are available to both non-members and members.=C2=A0</h2>=0A<p>=\n=0A\t<span style=3D\"color: rgb(228, 92, 39);\"><span style=3D\"font-size: 16px=\n;\"><strong>Guides to Doing Research in New York Counties</strong></span></s=\npan></p>=0A<p>=0A\tWith the help of a team of experienced volunteers, the NY=\nG&amp;B has begun to assemble individual guides to doing research in each o=\nf the 62 counties in the State of New York. =C2=A0Below is a list of County=\n Guides that have been assembled thus far.=C2=A0 Each Guide provides a comp=\nilation of resources available, with an emphasis on online resources, which=\n might be useful to someone doing research in a particular county.=C2=A0 Pl=\nease note that the inclusion of a link does not constitute an endorsement o=\nf its content or accuracy.=C2=A0 Although we have sought to include known, =\nreliable sources, we have leaned toward the side of inclusivity; while all =\nlinks might not be of equal value, an individual researcher is the best jud=\nge of what information might be of help to him or her.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tIt is o=\nur goal to refine and enhance the County Guides with feedback from our memb=\ners.=C2=A0 If you are knowledgeable about the genealogical resources of a p=\narticular county and would like to suggest additions or corrections to one =\nof our County Guide please send an email to: <a href=3D\"mailto:webmaster@ny=\ngbs.org\">webmaster@nygbs.org</a>.=C2=A0 If you would like to join our Count=\ny Guide volunteer team, please send an email to <a href=3D\"mailto:volunteer=\n@nygbs.org\">volunteer@nygbs.org</a>.</p>=0A<ul><li>=0A\t\tAlbany</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A\t\tBronx (Borough of the Bronx)</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tCayuga</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tDu=\ntchess</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tKings (Borough of Brooklyn)</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tNew York=\n (Borough of Manhattan)</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tOnondaga</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tPutnam</li>=\n=0A<li>=0A\t\tRensselaer</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tRockland</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tSuffolk</li>=\n=0A<li>=0A\t\tUlster</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tWestchester</li>=0A</ul><p>=0A\t<span sty=\nle=3D\"color: rgb(228, 92, 39);\"><span style=3D\"font-size: 16px;\"><strong>Re=\nsearch Aid Articles</strong></span></span></p>=0A<p>=0A\tFor many years, the=\n NYG&amp;B gathered the most useful articles published in the <em>New York =\nResearcher</em> along with other original material and presented them on it=\ns website under the title =E2=80=9CResearch Aids.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 Many of th=\ne most popular =E2=80=9CResearch Aids=E2=80=9D have been updated by the ori=\nginal authors and are listed below.=C2=A0 For other Research Aids, members =\ncan access an <a href=3D\"/researchaidarchive\">archive of Research Aids</a>.=\n Members may read the articles; non-members may view the titles of the arti=\ncles. Please note that the complete run of the <em>New York Researcher</em>=\n may now be found in our eLibrary. =C2=A0</p>=0A<ul><li>=0A\t\t375th Annivers=\nary of the Eendracht and Nieuw Nederland</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tThe 1911 State Lib=\nrary Fire and Its Effect on New York Genealogy</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tBefore the F=\nive Borough City: The Old Cities, Towns, and Villages That Came Together to=\n Form \"Greater New York\"</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tBrooklyn/Kings County Church Recor=\nds Since 1783</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tThe Calendar and Colonial New York</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A\t\tDivorce in New York</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tDutch Reformed Records of New York=\n City (Manhattan)</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tThe Eardeley Collection at the Brooklyn H=\nistorical Society</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tEpiscopal Records of New York City (Manha=\nttan)</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tKings County's Colonial Church Records</li>=0A<li>=0A=\n\t\tKings County Records from the St. Francis College Collection Now at the M=\nunicipal Archives of the City of New York</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tLittle Publicized=\n New York City Sources-- Bodies in Transit</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tLittle Publicize=\nd New York City Sources-- Common Council Filed Papers, 1670-1897</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A\t\tLittle Publicized New York City Sources-- The Landon Papers and Milita=\nry Records</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tLittle Publicized New York City Sources-- Minute=\ns of the Committee on Health 1798</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tLittle Publicized New Yor=\nk City Sources-- Vital Records from the Long-Island Star and the Brooklyn E=\nvening Star, 1809-1846</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tLutheran Records of New York City (M=\nanhattan)</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tMethodist Records of New York City (Manhattan)</l=\ni>=0A<li>=0A\t\tNew York 1890 Census Substitutes</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tNew York Cit=\ny Assessment Rolls 1699-1734</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tNew York City Vital Records</l=\ni>=0A<li>=0A\t\tNew York Probate Records Before 1787</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tNew York=\n Probate Records Since property=3D\"content:encoded\"><div>=0A<p>The =\nNYG&amp;B is hosting a walking tour of beautiful Woodlawn  Cemetery. First =\nopened in 1863, it is located in the Bronx at Webster  Avenue &amp; East 23=\n3rd Street. It is the final home of many of New York  City's historic figur=\nes such as Admiral David G. Farragut; author  Herman Melville; abolitionist=\n and women's rights activist Elizabeth Cady  Stanton; and journalist Joseph=\n Pulitzer.=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>We will be led on a 1.5 hour tour by NYG&amp;B me=\nmber and Woodlawn  historian Susan Olsen followed by a workshop on how to u=\nse the cemetery  databases. Registration is limited. <a href=3D\"https://new=\nyorkfamilyhistory.myshopify.com/collections/events/products/walking-tour-wo=\nodlawn-cemetery-non-member\" target=3D\"_blank\">Click here to register online=\n</a>.</p>=0A<p> For more information please call Lauren Maehrlein at (212) =\n755 - 8532 x211.=C2=A0</p></div>=0A</div></div></div><div class=3D\"field fi=\neld-name-field-datetime field-type-datetime field-label-above\"><div class=\n=3D\"field-label\">When:&nbsp;</div><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"=\nfield-item even\"><span class=3D\"date-display-single\">Saturday, September 15=\n, 2012 - <span class=3D\"date-display-start\">11:00am</span><span class=3D\"da=\nte-display-separator\"> - </span><span class=3D\"date-display-end\">1:30pm</sp=\nan></span></div></div></div><div class=3D\"field field-name-field-venue fiel=\nd-type-text field-label-above\"><div class=3D\"field-label\">Venue:&nbsp;</div=\n><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\">Woodlawn Cemeter=\ny - Webster Avenue &amp; East 233rd Street </div></div></div><div class=3D\"=\nfield field-name-field-sponsor field-type-text field-label-above\"><div clas=\ns=3D\"field-label\">Sponsor:&nbsp;</div><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=\n=3D\"field-item even\">The New York Genealogical & Biographical Society</div>=\n</div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=\n=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=\n=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a h=\nref=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D=\n\"/advertising\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Pres=\ns Room</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web De=\nsign</a></li>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/=\npages/The-New-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=\n=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images=\n/content-img/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=\n=0A            <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nof=\nollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content=\n-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A        =\n    <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  targe=\nt=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-fl=\nickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <d=\niv id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp; class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><div>Take a brea=\nk from the frenzy of election year politics and hear about the hearldry of =\nAmerican presidents - both hereditary arms of early U.S. presidents and als=\no more recently granted arms. Joseph McMillian will discuss the topic on Mo=\nnday, September 17th at the NYG&amp;B's headquarters on West 44th St., foll=\nowed by traditional refreshments sponsored by the Heraldry Committee of the=\n NYG&amp;B (John Shannon, chairman). Mr. McMillan is Director of Research a=\nt the American Heraldry Society in Washington, DC (<a href=3D\"http://www.am=\nericanheraldry.org\" target=3D\"_blank\">www.americanheraldry.org</a>). A care=\ner civil servant will over 28 years of service in the Department of Defense=\n, he is a series research fellow at the Institute of National Strategic Stu=\ndies. This event is free, but space is limited. Please make a reservation b=\ny sending an email to John Shannon at <a href=3D\"mailto:john.shannon@coaf.u=\ns\">john.shannon@coaf.us</a>.</div>=0A</div></div></div><div class=3D\"field =\nfield-name-field-datetime field-type-datetime field-label-above\"><div class=\n=3D\"field-label\">When:&nbsp;</div><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"=\nfield-item even\"><span class=3D\"date-display-single\">Monday, September 17, =\n2012 - <span class=3D\"date-display-start\">6:00pm</span><span class=3D\"date-=\ndisplay-separator\"> - </span><span class=3D\"date-display-end\">8:00pm</span>=\n</span></div></div></div><div class=3D\"field field-name-field-venue field-t=\nype-text field-label-above\"><div class=3D\"field-label\">Venue:&nbsp;</div><d=\niv class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\">The New York Geneal=\nogical &amp; Ms. Bursey-Sabo=\nurin has been Fraser Herald at the Canadian Heraldic Authority in Ottawa si=\nnce 1989.  She is the principal artist of the Authority.  Bursey-Sabourin h=\nas been responsible for the paintings made for the arms of the last five Go=\nvernors General of Canada and the Coat of arms of Canada.     The program i=\ns free but reservations are necessary as capacity is limited. New York Family History School FAQs           \t\t</h1>=0A       =\n=0A                  <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D=\n\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=\n=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-5\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" ab=\nout=3D\"/history-faq\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <d=\niv class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print=\n_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/5\" title=3D\"Display=\n a printer-friendly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"=\nwindow.open(this.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-=\nicon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhi=\nstory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-frie=\nndly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version=\n</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-=\nsummary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-=\nitem even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><h3 class=3D\"rtecenter\">=0A\t<img al=\nt=3D\"\" src=3D\"/sites/default/files/images/LOC80(1).jpg\" style=3D\"width: 618=\npx; height: 175px;\" /></h3>=0A<h3>=0A\tWhere is the New York Family History =\nSchool located?</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe school is a network of programs sponsored=\n by the New York Genealogical and Biographical Society, the New York Public=\n Library, the National Archives, and other organizations. The programs take=\n place in various locations, so the NYFHS is not located in any one place. =\nHowever, the founding organization, the NYG&amp;B, is located at 36 West 44=\nth Street in New York City.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tDoes the New York Family History =\nSchool offer a certificate program in genealogy?</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tNo. At least=\n not yet. The NYFHS courses are meant for people to take advantage of on an=\n a la carte basis, depending on each individual=E2=80=99s needs for trainin=\ng and information.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tHow do I register for classes?</h3>=0A<p>=\n=0A\tLook for the roster of courses on this web site, and then click through=\n to the sponsoring organization, and follow the instructions you find.</p>=\n=0A<h3>=0A\tDoes the New York Family History School offer online seminars?</=\nh3>=0A<p>=0A\tWe plan to offer online programs as soon as we can. At present=\n the online program is in the development stage.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tI=E2=80=99m =\ninterested in a class which I cannot attend.Can I receive a copy of the han=\ndouts?</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tPossibly. The individual instructors and their organiz=\national sponsors will decide that on a case-by-case basis.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tHo=\nw can I get in touch with a program presenter?</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tIf you cannot =\nattend the program where you will meet the presenter, contact the sponsorin=\ng organization.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tWhy do some classes have a fee and other clas=\nses do not?</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tPolicies for charging fees vary from one organiza=\ntion to another. For example, generally programs at the New York Public Lib=\nrary are free. Other organizations need to charge fees to cover their expen=\nses.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tI have basic questions about my research. Who can I cont=\nact for assistance?</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe New York Genealogical and Biographica=\nl Society maintains a <a href=3D\"/professional-genealogists\">list of contra=\nct researchers</a>.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tHow can my program be included in the cal=\nendar of the New York Family History School?</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tPlease contact t=\nhe New York Genealogical Society by email: <a href=3D\"mailto:education@nygb=\ns.org\">education@nygbs.org</a>.</p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A=\n  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=\n=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/pr=\nivacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of=\n Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a><=\n/li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <li=\n><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=\n=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogic=\nal-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank=\n\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\"=\n alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http:/=\n/twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img sr=\nc=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Tw=\nitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr=\n.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/=\nall/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  b=\norder=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        N=\new York Genealogical &amp;                <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"bl=\nock-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"=\ncontent\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-4\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=\n=3D\"/partners\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div cla=\nss=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"=\n><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/4\" title=3D\"Display a pri=\nnter-friendly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window=\n.open(this.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon p=\nrint-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.=\norg/sites/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly v=\nersion\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></=\nspan></span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summar=\ny field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item e=\nven\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><h2>The New York Genealogical and Biograp=\nhical Society, the Milstein Division of the New York Public Library, and th=\ne National Archives in New York City were the founding organizations. These=\n three entities began working together by combining the genealogical progra=\nms of the three institutions in one integrated calendar. Other genealogical=\n organizations are coming on board as partners.</h2>=0A<h3><a href=3D\"http:=\n//www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"http://www.n=\newyorkfamilyhistoryschool.org/sites/default/files/images/NYGB%20color.jpg\" =\ntitle=3D\"nygb_color_small\" style=3D\"width: 100px; height: 53px; float: left=\n;\" class=3D\"alignleft size-full wp-image-212\" /></a>The New York Genealogic=\nal and Biographical Society</h3>=0A<p>The NYG&amp;B operates from a headqua=\nrters office in midtown Manhattan. Some of its programs are held in the off=\nices, others are held elsewhere. Please check the program listing for locat=\nion. View information about <a href=3D\"/contact-us\">contacting the NYG&amp;=\nB</a>.</p>=0A<h3><a href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img sr=\nc=3D\"http://i41.tinypic.com/28sr3ix.jpg\" title=3D\"nypl_small\" style=3D\"widt=\nh: 100px; height: 61px; float: left;\" class=3D\"alignleft size-full wp-image=\n-218\" /></a>The New York Public Library</h3>=0A<p>The NYPL has a central re=\nsearch library in the Stephan A. Schwarzman Building on Fifth Avenue and 42=\n<sup>nd</sup> Street in midtown Manhattan, with other research libraries an=\nd branch libraries located elsewhere. The <a href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/lo=\ncations/schwarzman/milstein-division-us-history-local-history-genealogy\" ta=\nrget=3D\"_blank\">Milstein Division of United States History, Local History a=\nnd Genealogy</a> is located within this central research library.</p>=0A<h3=\n><a href=3D\"http://www.archives.gov/northeast/nyc/\" target=3D\"_blank\" rel=\n=3D\"attachment wp-att-219\"><img src=3D\"http://i42.tinypic.com/2v3hlw2.jpg\" =\ntitle=3D\"nara_small\" style=3D\"width: 100px; height: 42px; float: left;\" cla=\nss=3D\"alignleft size-full wp-image-219\" /></a>The National Archives at New =\nYork City</h3>=0A<p>The National Archives serves researchers in their Manha=\nttan offices, where they also conduct public programs.</p>=0A</div></div></=\ndiv>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      <=\n/article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A      =\n    <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/s=\nervice-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/adverti=\nsing\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a=\n></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a><=\n/li>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The=\n-New-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollo=\nw\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-im=\ng/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A         =\n   <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" targe=\nt=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-tw=\nitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=\n=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank=\n\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" a=\nlt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"co=\npyright\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp;            =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=\n=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      Benefits of Membership in the NYG&=\namp;B           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region =\nregion-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-s=\nystem\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-1\" clas=\ns=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/member-benefits\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Doc=\nument\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=\n=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyh=\nistory.org/print/1\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of this pag=\ne.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return false\" r=\nel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:=\nImage\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons=\n/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly=\n version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field f=\nield-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=\n=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded=\n\"><h2>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B is a membership organization, and new members are a=\nlways welcome.</h2>=0A<p>=0A\t<img alt=3D\"\" src=3D\"/sites/default/files/imag=\nes/MK17(3).jpg\" style=3D\"width: 589px; height: 188px;\" /></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tNYG=\n&amp;B Members receive:</h3>=0A<ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>A subscription t=\no <em>The Record</em></strong>, a distinguished quarterly scholarly journal=\n published continuously since 1870 and recognized as the most important jou=\nrnal for New York=C2=A0 genealogical research</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>A subscription to <em>The</em> <em>New York Researcher<=\n/em></strong>, a colorful quarterly review which features instructive artic=\nles on genealogical research techniques and resources; news from the fields=\n of genealogy and biography; announcements about the NYG&amp;B; book review=\ns; and a Genealogical Exchange where members may publish queries related to=\n their research</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Online, remo=\nte access to the NYG&amp;B=E2=80=99s growing collection of digitized resour=\nces</strong>, which include:</p>=0A<ul style=3D\"list-style-type: circle;\"><=\nli>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t\tAll issues of <em><strong>The Record</strong>, </em>which =\ncomprises the largest single collection of published material on families t=\nhat lived in New York State, as well as access to updated versions of Jean =\nWorden=E2=80=99s indexes to the <em>Record</em></p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A=\n\t\t\t\t\tThe complete run of <strong><em>The</em></strong> <em><strong>New York=\n Researcher</strong>, </em>along with a comprehensive table of contents and=\n surname index</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t\t<strong><em>Early American N=\newspapers Series I</em></strong>, with 350,000 fully searchable issues from=\n over 710 newspapers published from 1690-1876.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t=\n\t\t\t\t<strong>Searchable cemetery transcriptions and religious records</stron=\ng> that are unique to the NYG&amp;B =\nCollection; and Biographical sketches of NYG&amp;B members from the first h=\nalf of the 20<sup>th</sup> century plus, more exceptional material that is =\nbeing added</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t\t<strong>Digital books</strong> =\nfrom the series of volumes published as the NYG&amp;B Collections, plus sev=\neral entries in the WPA Historical Records Survey series</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t\tNumerous articles and guides to assist NYG&amp;B members in t=\nheir New York research, including the most popular <strong>Research Aid art=\nicles</strong> that have been updated by experts in the field, along with a=\nn archive of original Research Aids</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t\t<strong=\n>Original Guides</strong> to for a photoc=\nopy of a document that they have identified in the collections of the Milst=\nein Division of the New York Public Library, the Municipal Archives of New =\nYork City, or the National Archives =E2=80=93 New York. Paul=E2=80=99s Church, member biographies, and Reverend Schneider=E2=80=\n=99s baptism records</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Invitat=\nions to exclusive members-only events</strong></p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Early notification and discounts on NYG&amp;B programs =\noffered through the New York Family History School</strong></p>=0A</li>=0A<=\n/ul><ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Discounts on NYG&amp;B publications and pro=\nducts</strong></p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Up to four fr=\nee queries a year</strong> published in <em>The New York Researcher</em>.</=\np>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>A subscription to the NYG&amp=\n;B=E2=80=99s monthly eNews. </strong>The eNews informs you of upcoming even=\nts and provides time-sensitive information. Email addresses are never share=\nd or disclosed.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>=\nDiscounts on Y-chromosome DNA tests for men, and mitochondrial and autosoma=\nl DNA tests for men and women through Family Tree DNA.=C2=A0 </strong>If yo=\nu ARE a member in the NYG&amp;B, you may <a href=3D\"/DiscountDNA\">access th=\ne discount</a> now.<strong>=C2=A0 </strong>If you are NOT a member of the N=\nYG&amp;B, <a href=3D\"/node/367\">learn more</a> about this DNA testing oppor=\ntunity.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>A discou=\nnt of 30% on the purchase of membership to WorldVitalRecords.com</strong>, =\nwith access to more than 1.5 billion international and U.S. records and 1 b=\nillion newspaper articles.
