<article class=3D\"\">      =0A                =0A      =\n   <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      Volunteer=\ning Opportunities           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                  <div clas=\ns=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"b=\nlock block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"=\nnode-21\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/volunteer-opportunitie=\ns\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"conten=\nt\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"=\nhttp://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/21\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friend=\nly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.=\nhref); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-m=\nargin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/a=\nll/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" tit=\nle=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span=\n><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-lab=\nel-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" proper=\nty=3D\"content:encoded\"><p class=3D\"rtecenter\"><img src=3D\"/sites/default/fi=\nles/images/nygbs-img-content-9.jpg\" style=3D\"width: 595px; height: 150px;\" =\n/></p>=0A<h2><a name=3D\"top\" id=3D\"top\"></a>There are many ways to contribu=\nte your time and talents to forwarding the mission of the NYG&amp;B. We hav=\ne projects to build and enrich the eLibrary, projects to serve members, and=\n projects to support various NYG&amp;B activities. There is something of in=\nterest for everyone and=C2=A0something that matches your skill and experien=\nce.</h2>=0A<h3>Contents</h3>=0A<ul><li> <a href=3D\"#eLibrary\">Projects to E=\nnrich Our eLibrary</a></li>=0A<li> <a href=3D\"#Members\">Projects to Serve N=\nYG&amp;B Members</a></li>=0A<li> <a href=3D\"#Activities\">Project to Support=\n NYG&amp;B Activities</a></li>=0A</ul><h2><span style=3D\"font-size: 20px;\">=\nProjects to Enrich our eLibrary<a name=3D\"eLibrary\" id=3D\"eLibrary\"></a></s=\npan></h2>=0A<h3>Indexing</h3>=0A<p>The NYGB's team of indexers makes our gr=\nowing eLibrary searchable and accessible to our members. Indexing can be do=\nne from the convenience of your own home anywhere in the world. Volunteers =\nare sent scanned document pages by email from which they are able to easily=\n extract data into an Excel spreadsheet. Indexing of the 1855 New York Stat=\ne Census for Ward 17 is currently in progress. Future indexing projects inc=\nlude: Reverend Schneider's baptismal records; St. Paul's Church records; an=\nd St. Luke's Church records.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualifications:</strong> Abil=\nity to read handwriting; attention to detail; home computer with internet a=\nccess, Excel, and Adobe Acrobat Reader (a free downloadable program).</p>=\n=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commitment:</strong> two or more hours per mon=\nth.</p>=0A<h3>Proofreading</h3>=0A<p>Proofreaders are needed to verify the =\naccuracy of data entry by arbitrating any discrepancies in the duplicate in=\ndexes that are created for each document.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualifications:<=\n/strong> Ability to read handwriting; attention to detail; home computer wi=\nth internet access, Excel, and Adobe Acrobat Reader (a free downloadable pr=\nogram); ability to handle multiple files at one time. Can be done remotely,=\n but some on-site training is needed.</p>=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commi=\ntment:</strong> three months, two or more hours per week.</p>=0A<h3>Digital=\n Quality Control</h3>=0A<p>Quality controllers will verify that scanned doc=\numents are readable and in proper page order before they are uploaded to ou=\nr website.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualifications:</strong> Ability to read handwr=\niting; attention to detail; high comfort level with computers and digital d=\nocuments. On-site presence required.</p>=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commit=\nment: </strong>three months, four or more hours per week.</p>=0A<h3>Documen=\nt Scanning</h3>=0A<p>Volunteers will be trained to scan printed materials a=\nnd clean up previously scanned text and images.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualificat=\nions:</strong> Ability to read handwriting; attention to detail; high comfo=\nrt level with computers and digital documents. On-site presence required.</=\np>=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commitment:</strong> four or more hours per =\nmonth.</p>=0A<h3>Document Integration and Uploading</h3>=0A<p>Trained volun=\nteers will integrate and upload document collections and indexes to the eLi=\nbrary using CONTENTdm, the digital management collection software produced =\nby OCLC. On-site presence required.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualifications:</stron=\ng> High comfort level with computers and digital documents; previous experi=\nence with CONTENTdm and OCR helpful.</p>=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commit=\nment:</strong> three months, two or more hours per week.</p>=0A<h3>Digital =\nProject Leaders</h3>=0A<p>Digital project leaders are needed to create a st=\nrategy document and protocols for digitizing and indexing each document col=\nlection and to provide supervision to the volunteer team.</p>=0A<p><strong>=\nQualifications:</strong> Ability to read handwriting; attention to detail; =\nhigh comfort level with computers and digital documents. On-site presence r=\nequired.</p>=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commitment:</strong> six months, f=\nour or more hours per week.</p>=0A<h3>Digital Project Assistants</h3>=0A<p>=\nThe digital project assistants will be the primary contacts for each team o=\nf indexers. They will distribute the scanned document pages; collect comple=\nted spreadsheets and distribute them to the proofreaders; maintain a tracki=\nng document; and communicate as needed with individual indexers.</p>=0A<p><=\nstrong>Qualifications:</strong> Ability to read handwriting; attention to d=\netail; home computer with internet access, Excel, and Adobe Acrobat Reader =\n(a free downloadable program). Can be done remotely, but some on-site prese=\nnce is needed.</p>=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commitment:</strong> six mon=\nths, three or more hours per week.</p>=0A<p><a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP<=\n/a></p>=0A<h2><span style=3D\"font-size: 20px;\">Projects to Serve NYG&amp;B =\nMembers<a name=3D\"Members\" id=3D\"Members\"></a></span></h2>=0A<h3>Minisearch=\n - Member Lookups</h3>=0A<p>The NYG&amp;B has introduced a Minisearch servi=\nce for members.=C2=A0 While many members live outside the New York region a=\nnd cannot easily travel to our local repositories to make copies of documen=\nts, other members regularly conduct research at local repositories, such as=\n the Milstein Division of the NYPL and the Municipal or National Archives, =\nwhere they could copy the very information another member needs.=C2=A0 Our =\ngoal is to build a team of volunteers who are experienced in using local re=\npositories and willing to print copies of specific records =E2=80=93 e.g. g=\nenealogy excerpt, birth certificate, passenger arrival record =E2=80=93 tha=\nt a member has already identified.=C2=A0 This is a very direct way to help =\nyour fellow members.=C2=A0</p>=0A<p><strong>Suggested time commitment:</str=\nong> three months, two or more hours per month.</p>=0A<h3>Content Developme=\nnt for Website</h3>=0A<p>Volunteers can help make the new NYG&amp;B website=\n the best source for information on New York family history research by hel=\nping us develop new content. Among our goals is to compile a list of major =\nNew York repositories with descriptions of their holdings and links; compil=\ne a list of websites with online resources for New York State research; rea=\nch out to other organizations to expand the New York Family History School =\ncalendar of programs; create an index of and update the most valuable artic=\nles in Research Aids; create finding aids to selected portions of the NYG&a=\nmp;B collection at the Milstein Division.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualifications:<=\n/strong> Knowledge and experience of resources for New York family history =\nresearch; good writing skills; familiarity with the internet, Word, and Exc=\nel. Can be done remotely, but some on-site presence is needed.</p>=0A<p><st=\nrong>Suggested time commitment:</strong> three months, three or more hours =\nper week.</p>=0A<p><a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A<h2><span style=\n=3D\"font-size: 20px;\">Projects to Support NYG&amp;B Activities<a name=3D\"Ac=\ntivities\" id=3D\"Activities\"></a></span></h2>=0A<h3>Member Mailings</h3>=0A<=\np>Enjoy the company of other volunteers and staff as you stuff, seal, and s=\ntamp. No knowledge of technology required! Mailings take place on a rolling=\n basis throughout the year and volunteers are called as needed.</p>=0A<h3>R=\naiser's Edge Membership Database</h3>=0A<p>Do you have or wish to gain expe=\nrience in using Raiser's Edge, the world's most popular membership database=\n that is widely used by cultural organizations, schools, and other nonprofi=\nt organizations? Volunteers are needed to help enter data and generate repo=\nrts.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualifications:</strong> Attention to detail; facilit=\ny with database or spreadsheet programs; experience with Raiser's Edge help=\nful but not required; training available. On-site presence required.</p>=0A=\n<p><strong>Suggested time commitment:</strong> three months, two or more ho=\nurs per week.</p>=0A<h3>Event and Program Staffing</h3>=0A<p>Help man the c=\nheck-in table at programs and events, greet guests, and answer questions ab=\nout the NYG&amp;B.</p>=0A<h3>Event Coverage</h3>=0A<p>The NYG&amp;B has joi=\nned the social network with pages on Twitter=C2=A0and Facebook. Now volunte=\ners are needed to do timely write-ups of NYG&amp;B programs and events that=\n they attend and to supply photographs.</p>=0A<p><strong>Qualifications:</s=\ntrong> Good writing and/or photographic skills.</p>=0A<h3>Conference Booth =\nStaffing</h3>=0A<p>If you are planning to attend one of the national geneal=\nogy conferences, please consider signing up as a volunteer in the NYG&amp;B=\n booth.=C2=A0 The NYG&amp;B will have booths at the following upcoming conf=\nerences:=C2=A0 National Genealogical Society Family History Conference, Cin=\ncinnati, OH, May 9-12, 2012.=C2=A0 Federation of Genealogical Societies, Bi=\nrmingham, AL, Aug. 29-Sept. 1, 2012.=C2=A0 Suggested time commitment: one h=\nour or more.</p>=0A<p><a href=3D\"#top\">RETURN TO TOP</a></p>=0A</div></div>=\n</div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A     =\n </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A    =\n      <li><a       <article class=3D\"\">      =0A       =\n         =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A             =\n         Internship Opportunities           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A           =\n       <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-=\nmain\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=\n=0A    <div id=3D\"node-50\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/inte=\nrnships\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"=\ncontent\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a hr=\nef=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/50\" title=3D\"Display a printer-=\nfriendly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open=\n(this.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-=\nicon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/s=\nites/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly versio=\nn\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span>=\n</span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary fie=\nld-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" =\nproperty=3D\"content:encoded\"><p><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/=\nstructure/getinvolved/getinvolved-content-2.jpg\" alt=3D\"Get involved in the=\n history\" /></p>=0A<h2>Interns play a significant and valued role at the NY=\nG&amp;B. Unlike many internships, the work we offer interns is challenging =\nand real, and the work interns do makes an important and visible difference=\n. Consequently, the program attracts unusually well-qualified and energetic=\n participants.</h2>=0A<h3>Academic Internships</h3>=0A<p>The NYG&amp;B is p=\nleased to offer academic internships for school credit to:</p>=0A<ul><li>=\n=0A<p><strong>Graduate students</strong> in the fields of library and infor=\nmation science, archival management, and records management. =C2=A0</p>=0A<=\n/li>=0A<li>=0A<p><strong>College students</strong> in the fields of history=\n, American Studies, communications, digital media, and other relevant field=\ns.</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><p>Academic internships will be tailored to a student=\n=E2=80=99s academic needs and the NYG&amp;B=E2=80=99s institutional goals.=\n=C2=A0 Interested students should e-mail a resume and cover letter to <a hr=\nef=3D\"mailto:intern@nygbs.org\">intern@nygbs.org</a>. Interviews are require=\nd. Applications are accepted and reviewed on a rolling basis as internships=\n are available year-round.</p>=0A<h3>College and High School Internships</h=\n3>=0A<div>The NYG&amp;B is pleased to offer several six-week and eight-week=\n internships for college and high school students. Internships are typicall=\ny four days a week; college internships come with a stipend of $100 per wee=\nk.=C2=A0 While summer internships are the most popular, the NYG&amp;B welco=\nmes interns year-round and will work with students to accommodate their sch=\nool schedule. =C2=A0<br /><br /> Interns will play a key role in the develo=\npment of content for our publications and our website.=C2=A0 Specific tasks=\n include compiling, proofreading, and fact-checking guides to conducting re=\nsearch in New York State; preparing and uploading content -- from historica=\nl documents to digital books -- to the NYG&amp;B=E2=80=99s website; and ass=\nisting with membership, marketing, education, and administrative projects.=\n=C2=A0 Interns will be given hands-on opportunities to develop valuable ski=\nlls through exposure to the many aspects of digitizing documents, social me=\ndia research and marketing, website development and search engine optimizat=\nion, current and historical research, and the Raiser=E2=80=99s Edge, a memb=\nership database that is widely used by nonprofit organizations and schools.=\n=C2=A0 <br /><br /> As part of its commitment to engage young people in fam=\nily history research, the NYG&amp;B offers interns the option to spend up t=\no five hours per week on an independent research project relating to their =\nown family or community histories, under the guidance of NYG&amp;B staff.=\n=C2=A0</div>=0A<h3>Qualifications</h3>=0A<div>Successful candidates must de=\nmonstrate attention to detail, good organizational skills, a comfort with t=\nechnology, and an enthusiasm for history and research.=C2=A0 In addition, g=\nood writing skills and experience with social and digital media will be hel=\npful.=C2=A0 Training will be provided on the Raiser=E2=80=99s Edge database=\n and Content DM digital management system; any prior knowledge of these pro=\ngrams would be an asset.</div>=0A<h3>How to Apply</h3>=0A<p>Interested stud=\nents should e-mail a resume and cover letter to  <a href=3D\"mailto:intern@n=\nygbs.org\">intern@nygbs.org</a>. Interviews are required. Applications are a=\nccepted and reviewed on a rolling basis as internships are available year-r=\nound. =C2=A0</p>=0A<h3>How to Sponsor an Intern</h3>=0A<p>A number of NYG&a=\nmp;B supporters underwrite the stipends paid to interns. If you are interes=\nted in being a sponsor, please contact Cathy Michelsen at 212-755-8532 ext.=\n 208, or send an email to <a href=3D\"mailto:intern@nygbs.org\">intern@nygbs.=\norg.</a></p>=0A<p><br /><br /><br /></p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A=\n  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </=\ndiv>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D=\n\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Term=\ns of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising<=\n/a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A         =\n <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </u=\nl>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealog=\nical-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_bla=\nnk\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.pn=\ng\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http=\n://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img =\nsrc=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"=\nTwitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flic=\nkr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/site=\ns/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\" =\n border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A       =\n New York Genealogical &amp; v=\nersion</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text=\n-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"=\nfield-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><p>Joseph McMillan will speak=\n on the heraldry of American Presidents.  This will cover both hereditary a=\nrms of early US presidents and also more recent granted arms.  Mr. McMillan=\n is a governor-at-large of the American College of Heraldry.  A career civi=\nl servant with over 28 years of service in the Department of Defense, he is=\n a senior research fellow at the Institute for National Strategic Studies.=\n=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>The program is free but reservations are ne=\ncessary as capacity is limited.</p>=0A<p>Please call 212-755-8532 x211 for =\nreservations. =C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div></div><div class=3D\"field field-name=\n-field-datetime field-type-datetime field-label-above\"><div class=3D\"field-=\nlabel\">When:&nbsp;</div><div <div id=3D\"block-search-form\" class=3D\"block block-sea=\nrch\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <form action=3D\"/recordfu=\nndnonmbr\" method=3D\"post\" id=3D\"search-block-form\" form=\n-item-search-block-form\">=0A  <label class=3D\"element-invisible\" for=3D\"edi=\nt-search-block-form--2\">Search </label>=0A <input title=3D\"Enter the terms =\nyou wish to search for.\"     =0A                =0A      </aside>=0A       =\n     <article class=3D\"\">      =0A                =0A         <h1 class=3D\"=\ntitle\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      Guide to the Fundamentals=\n of Using The Record Online           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                 =\n <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" =\nclass=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <=\ndiv id=3D\"node-398\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/recordfundn=\nonmbr\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"co=\nntent\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=\n=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/398\" title=3D\"Display a printer-f=\nriendly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(=\nthis.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-i=\ncon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/si=\ntes/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version=\n\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span><=\n/span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary fiel=\nd-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" p=\nroperty=3D\"content:encoded\"><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-=\ntext-with-summary field-label-hidden\">=0A<div class=3D\"field-items\">=0A<div=\n class=3D\"field-item even\">=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t<span style=3D\"color:#000080;\">Log =\nin to view a members-only version of this document with additional search i=\nnstructions and links, which can be found in <em>The Record</em> section of=\n the \"Welcome to the eLibrary\" page of this website.</span></p>=0A<h2>=0A\t\t=\n\t\tContinuously published since 1870, the <em>New York Genealogical and Biog=\nraphical Record</em> is the second oldest genealogical journal in the count=\nry and one of the most distinguished. =C2=A0The entire run of <em>The Recor=\nd</em> comprised 567 issues as of July 2011 and forms the largest single co=\nllection of published material on families that lived in New York State.=C2=\n=A0 Access to the digital version of <em>The Record </em>is available exclu=\nsively to NYG&amp;B members.=C2=A0</h2>=0A<h3>=0A\t\t\t\tTwo Ways to Search <em=\n>The Record</em></h3>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t<em>The Record</em> is searchable by the =\nfollowing methods, which are best used in tandem:</p>=0A<h4>=0A\t\t\t\tWorden=\n=E2=80=99s Index to Family and Given Names</h4>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\tMrs. Jean D. Wo=\nrden painstakingly indexed over one million names that appeared in <em>The =\nRecord</em> between 1870 and 1998, providing an invaluable research tool th=\nat has been appreciated by genealogical scholars everywhere.=C2=A0=C2=A0 Th=\nis index is updated every year after the fall release of the annual index b=\ny volunteers and interns and forms the basis of a search engine that will s=\nimultaneously search every issue of <em>The Record</em> since 1870.=C2=A0 <=\nstrong>Advantages:</strong> The Worden=E2=80=99s search engine is particula=\nrly useful when searching for a name that is also a common word, such as Br=\nown or Farmer.=C2=A0 The search results will provide the volume and page nu=\nmbers wherever the name appears.</p>=0A<h4>=0A\t\t\t\tAdvanced Search</h4>=0A<p>=\n=0A\t\t\t\tThe Advanced Search function in the eLibrary will allow you to searc=\nh by an exact phrase or by keywords.=C2=A0=C2=A0 <strong>Advantages:</stron=\ng>=C2=A0 Advanced Search is particularly useful when searching for an artic=\nle by title, subject, or volume.=C2=A0 If you have used the Worden=E2=80=99=\ns search engine and want to go to a specific volume and page number, Advanc=\ned Search will take you there.=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\tPlease note: Mrs. Word=\nen did not index such material as library accession lists, book reviews, so=\nciety proceedings, and genealogical exchange (queries), which are covered i=\nn the volume indexes.=C2=A0 Nor did she index the names of witnesses to bap=\ntisms and marriages, which appear in the transcripts of church records. The=\nrefore, the thorough researcher may want to use Advanced Search to identify=\n any additional occurrences of a name.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\t\t\t\tIndexes to <em>The =\nRecord</em></h3>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\tAn Annual Index to names in each volume of <em=\n>The Record</em> has been released every October since 1870.=C2=A0 The firs=\nt 25 volumes were indexed only by surname, but from volume 26 on the indexe=\ns include every name.=C2=A0 If you want to search the annual index for a pa=\nrticular volume, you can use Advanced Search to go to the volume and the se=\nlect the issue.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\tIn addition to the annual index, the NYG&am=\np;B has published several specialized indexes to <em>The Record </em>throug=\nh the years<em>, </em>which are now available in our eLibrary<em>.=C2=A0 </=\nem>While the following indexes vary in terms of their scope, they can be a =\nsource of useful information to the researcher trying to mine the rich body=\n of information contained in <em>The Record</em></p>=0A<h4>=0A\t\t\t\t<em>The N=\new York Genealogical and Biographical Record 113 Years Master Index 1870-19=\n82</em></h4>=0A<div>=0A\t\t\t\tPublished by Mrs. Jean D. Worden in 1983, this b=\nook is a subject index to articles that appeared in <em>The Record</em> fro=\nm 1870-1982.=C2=A0 While it includes many index references to individuals, =\nit is not meant to be a full name index.</div>=0A<div class=3D\"rteindent1\">=\n=0A\t\t\t\t<strong>Strengths: </strong>Index to articles by subject</div>=0A<di=\nv class=3D\"rteindent1\">=0A\t\t\t\t<strong>Period covered: </strong>1870-1982 (F=\nor subsequent years, see Harry Macy=E2=80=99s <em>Subject Index</em>, which=\n follows.)</div>=0A<div>=0A\t\t\t\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<h4>=0A\t\t\t\t<em>Subject Index =\nto Articles in the New York Genealogical and Biographical Record 1983-2010 =\n</em><em>(Volumes 114-141)</em>, compiled by Harry Macy Jr., FASG, FGBS</h4>=\n=0A<div>=0A\t\t\t\tThis index is a continuation of Mrs. Jean D. Worden=E2=80=99=\ns <em>Master Index 1870-1982</em>. It consists of three parts: compiled gen=\nealogies and family records, indexed by principal surnames; source records =\nand collective genealogies, indexed by location; and other articles, indexe=\nd by subject.=C2=A0</div>=0A<div class=3D\"rteindent1\">=0A\t\t\t\t<strong>Streng=\nths: </strong>Index to articles by subject and location</div>=0A<div class=\n=3D\"rteindent1\">=0A\t\t\t\t<strong>Period covered: </strong>1983-2010.=C2=A0 Th=\nis index will be updated annually following the release of the Annual Index=\n to <em>The Record</em> in October.=C2=A0=C2=A0 (For previous years, see Mr=\ns. Jean D. Worden=E2=80=99s <em>Master Index</em> above.)</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=\n\t\t\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<h4>=0A\t\t\t\t<em>Index to Articles in The Record by Title a=\nnd by Author </em><span style=3D\"color:#ffffff;\"><strong><strong><span styl=\ne=3D\"background-color: rgb(128, 0, 128);\">COMING SOON</span></strong></stro=\nng></span></h4>=0A<div>=0A\t\t\t\tPreviously available only on CD, this index p=\nrovides a browsable and searchable list of titles and authors of articles t=\nhat have appeared in <em>The Record</em> from 1870 through 2001.=C2=A0</div>=\n=0A<div class=3D\"rteindent1\">=0A\t\t\t\t<strong>Strengths: </strong>Articles in=\ndexed by title and author</div>=0A<div class=3D\"rteindent1\">=0A\t\t\t\t<strong>=\nPeriod covered: </strong>1870-2001.=C2=A0 An updated version is in progress=\n and will be made available as soon as it is completed.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t\t\t=\n\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<h4>=0A\t\t\t\t<em>Worden=E2=80=99s Index to Family and Given N=\names (Browsable Version) </em><span style=3D\"color:#ffffff;\"><strong><span =\nstyle=3D\"background-color: rgb(128, 0, 128);\">COMING SOON</span></strong></=\nspan></h4>=0A<div>=0A\t\t\t\tPreviously available only on CD and covering the p=\neriod 1870-1998, this is a browsable and searchable index of more than one =\nmillion names that have been mentioned in <em>The Record</em> from 1870 thr=\nough the present.=C2=A0 It forms the basis of our Worden=E2=80=99s search e=\nngine.=C2=A0=C2=A0</div>=0A<div class=3D\"rteindent1\">=0A\t\t\t\t<strong>Strengt=\nhs: </strong>Family and given names</div>=0A<div class=3D\"rteindent1\">=0A\t\t=\n\t\t<strong>Period covered: </strong>1870 to the present.=C2=A0 Updated every=\n year after the fall annual index is released.</div>=0A<h3>=0A\t\t\t\tStandard =\nSource Abbreviations</h3>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\tIf you are reading an article publish=\ned in <em>The New York Genealogical and Biographical Record</em> between 19=\n33 and 1996, you will find that sources are cited in the text, and the cita=\ntions use a <a href=3D\"../../abbreviations\">standard set of abbreviations</=\na> or acronyms for major New York sources.=C2=A0 Beginning in 1996, sources=\n for <em>Record</em> articles are cited in footnotes.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t\t=C2=\n=A0</p>=0A</div>=0A</div>=0A</div>=0A<p>=0A\t=C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div></div>=\n  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A />=0A</xml><![endif]-->=0A<!--[if gte mso 10]><style>=0A /* Styl=\ne Definitions */=0A table.MsoNormalTable=0A\t{mso-style-name:\"Table Normal\";=\n=0A\tmso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;=0A\tmso-tstyle-colband-size:0;=0A\tmso-style-n=\noshow:yes;=0A\tmso-style-priority:99;=0A\tmso-style-qformat:yes;=0A\tmso-style=\n-parent:\"\";=0A\tmso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;=0A\tmso-para-margin:0in;=\n=0A\tmso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;=0A\tmso-pagination:widow-orphan;=0A\tfont=\n-size:11.0pt;=0A\tfont-family:\"Calibri\",\"sans-serif\";=0A\tmso-ascii-font-fami=\nly:Calibri;=0A\tmso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;=0A\tmso-fareast-font-family=\n:\"Times New Roman\";=0A\tmso-fareast-theme-font:minor-fareast;=0A\tmso-hansi-f=\nont-family:Calibri;=0A\tmso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;=0A\tmso-bidi-font-f=\namily:\"Times New Roman\";=0A\tmso-bidi-theme-font:minor-bidi;}=0A</style><p><=\n![endif]-->=0A<p class=3D\"MsoNormal\" style=3D\"margin-top: 6pt; text-align: =\njustify;\">=0A\t<span style=3D\"font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-seri=\nf&quot;;\">Anyone may submit a query, both members and non-members. There is=\n no charge for a query submitted online.</span></p>=0A<p class=3D\"MsoNormal=\n\" style=3D\"margin-top: 6pt; text-align: justify;\">=0A\t<span style=3D\"font-f=\namily: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\"><strong>First</strong>, c=\nlick on the \"Submit New Query\" tab.</span></p>=0A<p class=3D\"MsoNormal\" sty=\nle=3D\"margin-top: 6pt; text-align: justify;\">=0A\t<span style=3D\"font-family=\n: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\"><strong>Second,</strong> provi=\nde your name and email address. This information will NOT be displayed on t=\nhe website unless you type it into the query field below.</span></p>=0A<p c=\nlass=3D\"MsoNormal\" style=3D\"margin-top: 6pt; text-align: justify;\">=0A\t<spa=\nn style=3D\"font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\"><strong>=\nThird</strong>, in the field marked \"title,\" add the surname of the family =\nabout which you are submitting a query. In the database, queries are filed =\nalphabetically by surname.</span></p>=0A<p class=3D\"MsoNormal\" style=3D\"mar=\ngin-top: 6pt; text-align: justify;\">=0A\t<strong>Fourth</strong>, type the t=\next of your query in the indicated field. We suggest you keep your query to=\n about 100 words or less. To receive a response, you must include a way for=\n readers to contact you. An email address is best. Note that everything you=\n type into the query field will be published.</p>=0A<p class=3D\"MsoNormal\" =\nstyle=3D\"margin-top: 6pt; text-align: justify;\">=0A\tYou might model your qu=\nery on the example below. Providing <span style=3D\"font-family: &quot;Arial=\n&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\">known dates, places, and other identifying =\ninformation is helpful. Please do not use abbreviations.</span></p>=0A<p cl=\nass=3D\"MsoNormal\" style=3D\"margin-top: 6pt; text-align: justify;\">=0A\t<stro=\nng>The final step </strong>is for your query to be approved for posting. Qu=\neries will not be edited, but queries that do not relate to New York resear=\nch, advertisements, and non-genealogical queries will not be approved.</p>=\n=0A<h3>=0A\tExample of An Online Query</h3>=0A<p class=3D\"MsoNormal\" style=\n=3D\"\">=0A\t<span style=3D\"font-size: 12px;\"><b><span style=3D\"font-family: &=\nquot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\">HENDERSON-JACKSON.</span></b><spa=\nn style=3D\"font-family: &quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\"> Seeking=\n information on the parents of Nancy Henderson (born about 1765), who marri=\ned Robert Jackson in Schenectady in the Dutch Reformed Church, 1785. Nancy =\ndied in Chautauqua Co. in 1832. Might she be a daughter of John James Hende=\nrson of Schenectady? Children of Nancy and Robert: Maria, born 1786; John, =\nborn 1788; Cornelia, born 1791; Nicholas, born 1796; Jacob, born 1799; Mich=\nael, born 1801; Elizabeth, born 1803; Sarah, born 1806, based on Schenectad=\ny, Dorlach, Rhinebeck, and Woestina church records. All baptismal witnesses=\n are related to the paternal Jackson side. <i>Jane Doe, 776 East 86<sup>th<=\n/sup> Street, New York, NY 10028, </i><a href=3D\"mailto:jane.doe@aol.com\">j=\nane.doe@aol.com</a>.</span></span></p>=0A<h3>=0A\tSubmitting Queries to <em>=\nThe New York Researcher</em> (Magazine)</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe NYG&amp;B will co=\nntinue publishing queries from members of the NYG&amp;B=C2=A0 in <em>The Ne=\nw York Researche</em>r.=C2=A0 Please consult a recent issue of <em>The New =\nYork Researcher</em> for information, or send email to <a href=3D\"mailto:ed=\nucation@nygbs.org\">education@nygbs.org</a></p>=0A<p>=0A\tQueries sent for pr=\ninting in <em>The New York Researcher</em> will also be published online. H=\nowever, queries published online must be submitted separately for printing =\nin <em>The New York Researcher</em>.</p>=0A<p>\t=C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div></d=\niv>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </=\narticle>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A       =\n   <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/se=\nrvice-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertis=\ning\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a>=\n</li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></=\nli>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-=\nNew-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow=\n\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img=\n/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A          =\n  <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=\n=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twi=\ntter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=\n=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank=\n\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" a=\nlt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"co=\npyright\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp; Doherty</div><div><strong>Description:</strong> Seeking information abou=\nt My Grandparents  Thomas T Sullivan and Johanna Doherty. Thomas came to th=\ne New York in 1890 from Broadford Limerick He was born in 1873 baptised in =\nthe parish of Killeedy, Limerick. Johanna cane to New York in Sept 1906  sh=\ne was born in 1884 and based on the passenger log was suppose to go to Troy=\n NY to work on River Street for a Mrs Shallor. They married about 1908 and =\nhad their fisrt of 11 children in 1909. They settled in South Ozone Park qu=\neens in abt 1915. I am interested in finding out where and extactly when th=\ney were married and where they lived before 1915. d. 1901 (Binghamton)</div><div><strong>Desc=\nription:</strong> Looking for info on Nathaniel Scales, cordwainer (bootmak=\ner), whose obit said \"former well known resident of Horseheads.\"  Resided w=\nith his dau Jane Scales Watson and Son-in-law Maj. James Watson in Binghamt=\non at the time of his death.  He immigrated 1837 but unclear what port of e=\nntry although he is listed as Cordwainer in Hartford CT 1846 City Directory=\n (on Welles St) where his two Civil War Vet sons were born -- Thomas and Jo=\nseph (1842/1845, respectively).  Our questions include: 1) did Nathaniel co=\nme to either Hartford, CT or Binghamton/Horseheads NY to join other family =\nalready established? and 2) how did he come to hook up with the Watson fami=\nly b/c he lived with James father Nathan in Census 1860 and  James in Censu=\ns 1900.</div><div><strong>Hits:</strong>542</div><div><strong>Date Added:</=\nstrong>2012-05-08 14:30:43</div><div><h2>Answers</h2></div><div><p><a href=\n=3D'/queries'>Back to Queries list</a> OR <a href=3D'/queries/add/294'>Answ=\ner this Query</a></p></div></div>  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </art=\nicle>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          =\n<li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/servi=\nce-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising=\n\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></l=\ni>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=\n=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New=\n-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  =\ntarget=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/ic=\non-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <=\na href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D=\n\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitte=\nr.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"h=\nttp://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><im=\ng src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D=\n\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyrig=\nht\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp; d. 1901 (Binghamton)</div><div><strong>Desc=\nription:</strong> Looking for info on Nathaniel Scales, cordwainer (bootmak=\ner), whose obit said \"former well known resident of Horseheads.\"  Resided w=\nith his dau Jane Scales Watson and Son-in-law Maj. James Watson in Binghamt=\non at the time of his death.  He immigrated 1837 but unclear what port of e=\nntry although he is listed as Cordwainer in Hartford CT 1846 City Directory=\n (on Welles St) where his two Civil War Vet sons were born -- Thomas and Jo=\nseph (1842/1845, respectively).  Our questions include: 1) did Nathaniel co=\nme to either Hartford, CT or Binghamton/Horseheads NY to join other family =\nalready established? and 2) how did he come to hook up with the Watson fami=\nly b/c he lived with James father Nathan in Census 1860 and  James in Censu=\ns 1900.</div><div><strong>Hits:</strong>893</div><div><strong>Date Added:</=\nstrong>2012-05-08 14:30:42</div><div><h2>Answers</h2></div><div><p><a href=\n=3D'/queries'>Back to Queries list</a> OR <a href=3D'/queries/add/293'>Answ=\ner this Query</a></p></div></div>  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </art=\nicle>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          =\n<li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/servi=\nce-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising=\n\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></l=\ni>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=\n=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New=\n-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  =\ntarget=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/ic=\non-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <=\na href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D=\n\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitte=\nr.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"h=\nttp://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><im=\ng src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D=\n\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyrig=\nht\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp; version</a></span></spa=\nn><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-la=\nbel-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" prope=\nrty=3D\"content:encoded\"><h2>=0A\tAll items donated by the New York Genealogi=\ncal and Biographical Society to the New York Public Library may be found at=\n its Stephen A. Schwarzman Building, which is located at Fifth Avenue and 4=\n2nd Street in New York City.=C2=A0 Much of the collection may be found in t=\nhe Irma and Paul Milstein Division of United States History, Local History =\nand Genealogy, Room 121; other portions may be found in the Microforms Sect=\nion, Room 100; the Map Division, Room 117; and the Manuscript Division, Roo=\nm 328.=C2=A0</h2>=0A<h3>=0A\tPlease note that some material is stored offsit=\ne and, therefore, may not be immediately available; these items will be ide=\nntified in the Catalog as \"Offsite-Request in Advance.\" To submit a request=\n in advance, send an email to <a href=3D\"mailto:histref@nypl.org\">histref@n=\nypl.org</a>.</h3>=0A<h4>=0A\t=C2=A0</h4>=0A<h4>=0A\t<u>Search the NYPL Catalo=\ng</u></h4>=0A<div>=0A\tAll NYG&amp;B materials have been added to the Librar=\ny=E2=80=99s online Catalog at <a href=3D\"http://catalog.nypl.org/search\">ht=\ntp://catalog.nypl.org/search</a></div>=0A<div>=0A\tIn the Catalog, you can s=\nearch by Keyword, if title is not known, or by exact Title or Author.=C2=A0=\n</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tSubject heading searches can be u=\nseful and a bit more focused.=C2=A0 For example, if you are looking for fam=\nily histories, try a Subject search for: <em>surname family</em></div>=0A<d=\niv>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 <em>example</em>: Bacon Family</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=\n=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tFor location, try a Subject search for: <em>locatio=\nn</em></div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 <em>example</em>: Rockland County N=\n.Y. Genealogy</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Buffalo N.Y. Genealo=\ngy</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 =C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 New Jersey Genealogy</div>=0A<di=\nv>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tHowever, Keyword searching can work just fine=\n too.=C2=A0 There is also an Advanced Search option on the left-hand menu w=\nhich allows you to narrow your search to a particular kind of material (e.g=\n. book, manuscript, microform, etc.)=C2=A0 Additional details, especially f=\nor manuscript-type materials, can also be searched at \"Find Archival Materi=\nals\": =C2=A0<a href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/find-archival-materials\">http://=\nwww.nypl.org/find-archival-materials</a></div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<h=\n4>=0A\t<u>Find NYG&amp;B Titles</u></h4>=0A<div>=0A\tTitles donated by the NY=\nG&amp;B retain =E2=80=9CNYGB=E2=80=9D as part of their call numbers.=C2=A0 =\nFor example, you can search <a href=3D\"http://catalog.nypl.org/search%7ES1/=\n?searchtype=3Dc&amp;searcharg=3Dnygb+map&amp;searchscope=3D1&amp;SORT=3DD&a=\nmp;extended=3D1&amp;searchlimits=3D&amp;searchorigarg=3Dcnygb+man\">NYGB Map=\n</a> to see all the NYGB maps in the Map Division, or<a href=3D\"http://cata=\nlog.nypl.org/search%7ES1/?searchtype=3Dc&amp;searcharg=3DNYGB+coll&amp;sear=\nchscope=3D1&amp;sortdropdown=3D-&amp;SORT=3DD&amp;extended=3D1&amp;searchli=\nmits=3D&amp;searchorigarg=3DcMssCol+NYGB\"> NYGB Coll</a> to search a geneal=\nogist's papers.=C2=A0=C2=A0 Manuscripts follow a different convention: <a h=\nref=3D\"http://catalog.nypl.org/search%7ES1/?searchtype=3Dc&amp;searcharg=3D=\nMssCol+NYGB&amp;searchscope=3D1&amp;sortdropdown=3D-&amp;SORT=3DD&amp;exten=\nded=3D1&amp;SUBMIT=3DSearch&amp;searchlimits=3D&amp;searchorigarg=3DcMssCol=\n+NYGB\">MssCol NYGB</a>.=C2=A0=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=\n=0A\tWhile items from the collection list the New York Genealogical and Biog=\nraphical Society Collection as an additional author, it is not possible to =\nobtain a complete list of NYG&amp;B titles from the NYPL Catalog through a =\nsearch on Author because the NYPL Catalog has a search result limit of 32,0=\n00.=C2=A0</div>=0A<h4>=0A\t=C2=A0</h4>=0A<h3>=0A\t<strong>Get Help</strong>:=\n=C2=A0 If you are unable to find an item that you believe should be in the =\nNYPL catalog, please contact the staff of the Milstein Division at <a href=\n=3D\"mailto:histref@nypl.org\">histref@nypl.org</a> or 212-930-0828.</h3>=0A<=\n/div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A id=3D\"main\" rol=\ne=3D\"main\" class=3D\"clearfix\">=0A            <aside>=0A                =0A =\n               =0A                =0A      </aside>=0A            <article =\nclass=3D\"\">      =0A                =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=3D\"p=\nage-title\">=0A                      Resources of the New York Public Librar=\ny of Special Interest to Family Researchers           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A =\n                 <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"blo=\nck-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"c=\nontent\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-29\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=\n=3D\"/librarycollection\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A =\n <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"pr=\nint_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/29\" title=3D\"Dis=\nplay a printer-friendly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=\n=3D\"window.open(this.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"pr=\nint-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfami=\nlyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-=\nfriendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly ver=\nsion</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-w=\nith-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"fi=\neld-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><p>=0A\t<img alt=3D\"Milstein Div=\nision\" src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/structure//libraryhead-content=\n-1.jpg\" /></p>=0A<h2>=0A\tThe Irma and Paul Milstein Division of U.S. Histor=\ny, Local History &amp; Genealogy, pictured above and located in the Stephen=\n A. Schwarzman Building at Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street, New York City, is =\nthe centerpiece of one of the great genealogical resources in the world.=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0</h2>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe vast resources of the NYPL that are of obvious=\n interest to genealogists and family historians exist in the Milstein Divsi=\non and a range of other locations in the NYPL. This page is an introduction=\n.=C2=A0</h3>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe Milstein Division of the NYPL</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe<=\na href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/locations/schwarzman/milstein-division-us-his=\ntory-local-history-genealogy\" target=3D\"_blank\"> Milstein Division</a> coll=\nects genealogical material related to New York City, state, and region, but=\n the collection goes <em>far beyond that</em> and is actually national and =\ninternational in scope. The collection includes books, serials, microforms,=\n vertical files, genealogical charts, photographic and negative collections=\n, postcards documenting United States local views,=C2=A0 pamphlets and othe=\nr ephemera.=C2=A0 The Milstein Division is located in Room 121 in the Steph=\nen A. Schwarzman Building at 42nd Street and Fifth Avenue.=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\t<strong>Online Resources</strong></p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe Milstein Divsion off=\ners basic resources in open stacks and computer terminals at the study tabl=\nes where patrons may access dozens of subscription databases such as Ancest=\nry.com, Fold3 (formerly Footnote), HeritageQuest, ProQuest, and AmericanAnc=\nestors.org,</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>Microform Resources</strong></p>=0A<p>=0A\t=\nMicroform Room 119 facilitates self-service access to the many important mi=\ncroform genealogical resources including some that are not yet online such =\nas New York State Census Records; directories from New York City and other =\ncities and towns throughout the tri-state area; and New York City vital rec=\nord indexes.=C2=A0</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe Lionel Pincus and Princess Firyal Map =\nDivision of the NYPL</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe <a href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/locat=\nions/schwarzman/map-division\" target=3D\"_blank\">Lionel Pincus and Princess =\nFiryal Map Division</a> holds one of the world=E2=80=99s largest, most exte=\nnsive, and most diverse collections of maps.=C2=A0 An enormous collection o=\nf maps of New York City and state is online and is an extraordinarily rich =\nsource for genealogical discovery. The reading room, an architectural <em>t=\nour de force</em>, offers open shelf reference books and computer workstati=\nons with access to map-related databases. The Map Division is a leader in v=\nery advanced use of digital mapping and map research techniques which will =\npowerfully impact genealogy.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tManuscripts and Archives Divisio=\nn of the NYPL</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe <a href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/locations/sc=\nhwarzman/manuscripts-division\" target=3D\"_blank\">Manuscripts and Archives D=\nivision </a>holds over five linear miles of archival material in over 3,000=\n collections, including papers, photographs, recordings, film and video, an=\nd other types of records. A particular strength of the Division are the 18t=\nh - 20th century papers and records of individuals, families, and organizat=\nions from the New York region.=C2=A0=C2=A0 A recent addition are the Civil =\nWar era records of the United States Sanitary Commission.=C2=A0 A mention o=\nf the Records of Fiorello H. LaGuardia, Robert Moses, the Emigrant Savings =\nBank, and the New York Central Railroad just barely scratches the surface.=\n=C2=A0</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe Rose Reading Room in the Schwarzman Building</h3>=\n=0A<p>=0A\tMany people going to the Schwarzman Building of the NYPL for its =\n<em>specialized</em> collections forget that the majestic and historic Rose=\n Reading Room contains enormously useful reference material relevant to gen=\nealogy and family history. The forty thousand plus reference collections ar=\ne on open shelves and can be browsed and include standard reference works u=\nseful to genealogists and also dictionaries, encyclopedias, biographies, an=\nd indexes. This facility has self-service photocopiers, a copy and scanning=\n service, internet access, and several dozen desktop computers.</p>=0A<h3>=\n=0A\tMicroforms Reading Room</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tPart of the General Research Divi=\nsion, this room is located in the Schwarzman Building. The collecction of m=\nicroforms is vast and includes periodicals, monographs, pamphlets, city dir=\nectories, and much else. The newspaper collection is enormous, and includes=\n many New York City and New York regional and local papers. The NYPL websit=\ne has exceptionally helpful online finding guides to its newspaper holdings=\n.</p>=0A<h3>=0A\tDorot Jewish Division of the NYPL</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tThis divi=\nsion contains a highly important collection of=C2=A0 Hebraica and Judaica.=\n=C2=A0 The collection is global in scope and has strength in Jews in the U.=\nS, and in New York in the age of immigration.</div>=0A<h3>=0A\tThe Schomburg=\n Center for Research in Black Culture</h3>=0A<p>=0A\tThe Schomburg Center is=\n a research facility covering the global African and African diasporan expe=\nriences. The center is rich in material relating to New York City and state=\n black history, culture, families, neighborhoods, and institutions. The fac=\nility offers a General Research and Reference Division, manuscripts, rare b=\nooks, art in many media, photographs, prints, regordings, and moving images=\n. The Schomburg Center also offers exhibitions and educational programs. Th=\ne Center is located in Harlem at 515 Malcolm X Boulevard.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<img=\n alt=3D\"Milstein Division\" src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/structure/=\n/libraryhead-content-2.jpg\" /></p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =\n=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A=\n    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/priva=\ncy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of Se=\nrvice</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a></li>=\n=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <li><a =\nhref=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=0A   =\n     <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogical-Bio=\ngraphical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img=\n src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\" alt=\n=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://twi=\ntter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D=\n\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitte=\nr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr.com=\n/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/=\nthemes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  borde=\nr=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        New Y=\nork Genealogical &amp; Biographical Society - NYG&amp;B <br />=0A        Co=\npyright 2011=0A      </div>=0A    </footer>=0A  </div><!-- /#container -->=\n=0A  </body>=0A</html>=0A=0A", "code": 200, "level": 2, "url": "http://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/librarycollection", "text": "guide to the resources of the NYPL for genealogists", "time": 1.3364191055297852, "redirect_urls": [], "headers": {"Content-Length": "5581", "X-Drupal-Cache": "MISS", "Content-Encoding": "gzip", "Expires": "Sun, 19 Nov 1978 05:00:00 GMT", "Vary": "Cookie,Accept-Encoding", "Server": "Apache", "Last-Modified": "Fri, 29 Jun 2012 23:42:22 +0000", "Connection": "close", "Etag": "\"1341013342-1\"", "Link": "</node/29>; <div id=3D\"block-search-form\" class=3D\"block block-search\">=0A=0A=\n    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <form action=3D\"/member-gettingstart=\ned\" method=3D\"post\" id=3D\"search-block-form\" accept-charset=3D\"UTF-8\"><div>=\n<div class=3D\"container-inline\">=0A      <h2 class=3D\"element-invisible\">Se=\narch form</h2>=0A    <div class=3D\"form-item form-type-textfield form-item-=\nsearch-block-form\">=0A  <label class=3D\"element-invisible\" for=3D\"edit-sear=\nch-block-form--2\">Search </label>=0A <input title=3D\"Enter the terms you wi=\nsh to search for.\" type=3D\"text\" id=3D\"edit-search-block-form--2\" name=3D\"s=\nearch_block_form\" value=3D\"\" size=3D\"15\" maxlength=3D\"128\" class=3D\"form-te=\nxt\" />=0A</div>=0A<div class=3D\"form-actions form-wrapper\" id=3D\"edit-actio=\nns\"><input type=3D\"submit\" id=3D\"edit-submit\" name=3D\"op\" value=3D\"Search\" =\nclass=3D\"form-submit\" /></div><input type=3D\"hidden\" name=3D\"form_build_id\"=\n value=3D\"form-TdKEGclr5QZoywLvo8JFlOlYJx99uZum58sggGB-fss\" />=0A<input typ=\ne=3D\"hidden\" name=3D\"form_id\" value=3D\"search_block_form\" />=0A</div>=0A</d=\niv></form>  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A    </header>=0A    <nav class=3D\"=\nmain\">=0A      <ul>=0A                <li class=3D\"research\"><a
