href=3D\"/giving-op=\nportunities\">Give</a></li>=0A      </ul>=0A    </nav>=0A    <div id=3D\"main=\n\" role=3D\"main\" class=3D\"clearfix\">=0A            <aside>=0A                =\n=0A                =0A                =0A      </aside>=0A            <arti=\ncle class=3D\"\">      =0A                =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=\n=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      Getting Started on Your Family His=\ntory           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region r=\negion-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-sy=\nstem\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-113\" cla=\nss=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/member-gettingstarted\" typeof=3D\"f=\noaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <spa=\nn class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyork=\nfamilyhistory.org/print/113\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of=\n this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return=\n false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=\n=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/pr=\nint/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer=\n-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=\n=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\">=\n<div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"conte=\nnt:encoded\"><table align=3D\"right\" border=3D\"0\" cellpadding=3D\"1\" cellspaci=\nng=3D\"1\" style=3D\"width: 328px; height: 408px;\"><tbody><tr><td style=3D\"wid=\nth: 15px;\">=0A\t\t\t\t=C2=A0</td>=0A<td style=3D\"width: 299px;\">=0A<h2>=0A\t\t\t\t\t=\n<img alt=3D\"\" src=3D\"/sites/default/files/images/6035670221_71d9852312_b.jp=\ng\" style=3D\"width: 279px; height: 369px; float: right;\" /></h2>=0A</td>=0A<=\n/tr></tbody></table><h2>=0A\tAre you considering working on your family hist=\nory or are you just getting started? Here are some basic building blocks th=\nat will help get you off on the right foot as you begin exploring this fasc=\ninating and rewarding activity.</h2>=0A<h3>=0A\tBegin with Yourself</h3>=0A<=\ndiv>=0A\tThe recommended way to begin tracing your genealogy is to begin wit=\nh yourself and work from there, one generation at a time. You must work fro=\nm the known into the unknown. All too often people seek to prove a connecti=\non to an important event, or to a famous person because of a shared surname=\n, but unless you have some strong family history or documentation indicatin=\ng this connection, this approach can end in disappointment.</div>=0A<div>=\n=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tBefore seeking out information from other famil=\ny members, or visiting archives, or going online for data, carefully review=\n what information you know, or think you know, about your family. This will=\n be the foundation upon which your family history will be built.</div>=0A<h=\n3>=0A\tInterview Family Members</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tSpeak with as many family me=\nmbers as you can.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<ul><li>=0A\t\tWhere they w=\nere born?</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tWhat were their parents=E2=80=99 names?</li>=0A<l=\ni>=0A\t\tWho were their siblings?</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tWhere did they live?</li>=\n=0A<li>=0A\t\tWhat were their occupations?</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tWhat were their re=\nligious traditions?</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tWhat particular family traits may have =\nbeen passed down?</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\tWhat sort of illnesses do they remember o=\nccurring among family members?</li>=0A</ul><div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A=\n\tMany of these questions cannot be answered by documentation, but only by t=\nhe person you=E2=80=99re interviewing. You may have elderly relatives who m=\nay have family information that they=E2=80=99ve never discussed because the=\ny were never asked. For obvious reasons speak to them now.</div>=0A<div>=0A=\n\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tYou may=C2=A0eventually be able to find out where =\nyour grandparents lived or who their parents were, but no records will tell=\n you about personal aspects of their lives. For that sort of information yo=\nu need to speak to them directly or to people who knew them well. Many peop=\nle studying their family history began their research when they were older =\n=E2=80=93 after their families were raised or after they=E2=80=99d retired.=\n This is when they had the time to pursue what can be a very time consuming=\n interest. Of course, by then there were few if any older people for them t=\no speak to.</div>=0A<h3>=0A\tOrganize Your Information</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tBegin=\n by creating charts outlining your family members and their relationships t=\no each other, using family tree charts and family group sheets. Download bl=\nank forms for free at many locations online, including <a href=3D\"http://ww=\nw.genealogysearch.org/free/forms.html\" target=3D\"_blank\">this one</a>.</div>=\n=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tIt=E2=80=99s never too soon to organize the data you=\n=E2=80=99re collecting on your computer in a specially designed genealogy f=\normat. Don=E2=80=99t wait until you=E2=80=99re overwhelmed with the sheer v=\nolume of information; begin your record-keeping as soon as you begin your r=\nesearch.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tThere are many record-keeping packages =\navailable on the market at nominal cost. For PC users, the choices are nume=\nrous: Ancestral Quest, Family Tree Maker, Legacy, The Master Genealogist, a=\nnd RootsMagic, among others. =C2=A0For Apple users, the choices are fewer. =\nThe main ones for the Macintosh are Reunion and Family Tree Maker for Mac. =\nYou can download a free copy of Personal Ancestry File (PAF) through the <a=\n href=3D\"https://www.familysearch.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\">FamilySearch</a> =\nsite.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tThere is plenty of information that compar=\nes packages. The key is to make sure that the package you acquire has GEDCO=\nM functionality. This permits you to move your data from one program to ano=\nther without reentering your data. It also allows you to share it with othe=\nrs.</div>=0A<h3>=0A\tDocument as You Go</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tDon=E2=80=99t expect=\n to remember where each bit of information came from. Record the person=E2=\n=80=99s name, date, and place when interviewing a family member. When you b=\negin using the internet or archival material always record not only the spe=\ncific source (website, book, manuscript) that the data came from, but also =\nwhere you found that source (for example: <a href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/lo=\ncations/schwarzman/milstein-division-us-history-local-history-genealogy\" ta=\nrget=3D\"_blank\">The Milstein Division</a>, New York Public Library). There =\nwill invariably be times when you=E2=80=99ll look for additional informatio=\nn from a source you=E2=80=99ve already consulted. Make finding that source =\nagain as easy as possible.</div>=0A<h3>=0A\tUsing Census Records</h3>=0A<div>=\n=0A\tCensus records are an extremely valuable source of family information, =\nproviding a wide range of data and placing family members together in a spe=\ncific location. Searching the census is a good beginning point in family hi=\nstory.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tAlthough the earliest censuses (1790-1840=\n) were simply a count of the number of people in a given area, beginning in=\n 1850 the census listed every member of a household, and later census recor=\nds included much more information, including relationship to head of househ=\nold, exact ages, place of birth, occupation, etc.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=\n=0A\tFederal census records are available for all the states and territories=\n from the very first taken in 1790 through 1930, which is the last to have =\nbeen released. Due to privacy regulations, there is a 72 year waiting perio=\nd from the time a census is taken until it can be made generally accessible=\n. The 1940 Federal Census will be released online on April 2, 2012.</div>=\n=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tCensus records are available online through databases=\n such as:</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<ul><li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"http://ww=\nw.heritagequestonline.com/hqoweb/library/do/index\" target=3D\"_blank\">Herita=\ngeQuestOnline</a>, which charges a fee, but can often be accessed at your l=\nocal libraries.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.ancestry.com/home/lo/=\nmerlin?abname=3DMerlinFreeImageTest_26052011&amp;abvalue=3DLoggedout_image_=\npreview26052\" target=3D\"_blank\">Ancestry.com</a>, a for-profit genealogical=\n information provider (also charges a fee, but may be available at local li=\nbraries).</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.footnote.com/\" target=3D\"_b=\nlank\">Fold3 (formerly FootNote)</a> (Now owned by Ancestry.com) (fee)</li>=\n=0A<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.worldvitalrecords.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\"=\n>World Vital Records</a> (fee)</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<a href=3D\"https://www.famil=\nysearch.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\">Family Search</a>, a=C2=A0website maintaine=\nd by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints,=C2=A0offers a transcr=\niption of the 1880 federal census (free).</li>=0A</ul><div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=\n=0A<div>=0A\tMany targeted transcriptions and/or images of census records ar=\ne available through smaller organizations, such as county genealogical soci=\neties or the like. Some require membership to access those records.<br />=\n=0A\tSeveral states, including New York and New Jersey, also conducted censu=\nses on the =E2=80=9C5=E2=80=9D year of each decade. New Jersey=E2=80=99s we=\nre taken through 1915 and New York through 1925. Most of these records are =\nnot available online, although some are beginning to be made available.</di=\nv>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tPlease be aware when working with census records th=\nat they are rife with errors. Although you can almost always glean valuable=\n information from them, never accept census records as necessarily accurate=\n.=C2=A0 Names are often misspelled or completely incorrect, ages, birthplac=\nes, occupations may be incorrect, and family members may be left out.</div>=\n=0A<h3>=0A\tSearching for Records</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tEventually you will need t=\no search for documentation. What sort of information do you need to find to=\n trace your family and where can you find it?</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br /><em>Ty=\npes of Records</em></div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<ul><li>=0A\t\t<strong>Bi=\nrth date, birth place, parents:</strong> Birth certificates, religious reco=\nrds, death certificates.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<strong>Death date, place of death=\n:</strong> SSDI (see below), death certificates, obituaries</li>=0A<li>=0A\t=\n\t<strong>Marriage:</strong>=C2=A0 Marriage certificates, religious records,=\n newspaper articles, census records, photographs.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<strong>C=\nhildren:</strong> Birth certificates, obituaries, wills, census records, pr=\nobate.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<strong>Medical/Genetic information:</strong> Medica=\nl records, military records, DNA testing (eye color, inherited diseases).=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<str=\nong>Life/interests: </strong>divorce records, newspapers, court records, ob=\nituaries, diaries, journals, letters.</li>=0A<li>=0A\t\t<strong>Residences:</=\nstrong> City directories, real estate transactions, voting registrations, w=\nills, deeds.</li>=0A</ul><div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<em>Sources of In=\nformation</em></div>=0A<ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>City directories</strong=\n>, which were the equivalent of telephone directories before there were pho=\nnes. Although the information they provide is limited to name, occupation, =\nand address, and until the early 20th century women weren=E2=80=99t listed =\nunless they were widows or were in business for themselves, they are often =\nthe only way to locate a family. Another benefit of city directories is tha=\nt they provide lists of organizations, schools, officials, voting districts=\n, churches.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Religious records</strong=\n> can provide more information than almost any other source, but before you=\n can uncover these records you=E2=80=99ll need to figure which institution =\nyour family attended. City directories can narrow down where your family at=\ntended religious services by providing lists of houses of worship in the ne=\nighborhood in which=C2=A0they lived. Not all religious records are readily =\navailable, but several of the various repositories in New York City, includ=\ning the Milstein Division of the New York Public Library, have large collec=\ntions of church records among their holdings. The Church of Jesus Christ of=\n Latter-day Saints has a large collection of religious records, many of whi=\nch are available online; others may be accessed on microfilm through their =\nlocal LDS Family History Centers.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Vit=\nal records</strong> are one of the most important resources. Birth records,=\n however, until the late 1800s, were not consistently kept. Some towns in N=\new England kept birth records from the early 1700s, others kept none until =\nmandated by the state. Marriages were generally kept by religious instituti=\nons or by the officiating clergyperson. Those marriages performed by a just=\nice of the peace or mayor, however, were probably recorded in the town reco=\nrds. Because a body needed to be disposed of, deaths were usually recorded =\nin town records, even in the earliest years. <a href=3D\"http://www.ancestry=\n.com/home/lo/merlin?abname=3DMerlinFreeImageTest_26052011&amp;abvalue=3DLog=\ngedout_image_preview26052\" target=3D\"_blank\">Ancestry.com</a> has a signifi=\ncant collection of vital records. Indexes of vitals for New York City and t=\nhe immediate surrounding area can be are being made available online throug=\nh the efforts of volunteers of the <a href=3D\"http://www.germangenealogygro=\nup.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\">German Genealogy Group</a> and the <a href=3D\"ht=\ntp://www.italiangen.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\">Italian Genealogy Group</a>.</p>=\n=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Court records</strong> include=C2=A0will=\ns, deeds, mortgages, probate, law suits, orphans court, trials. Never assum=\ne that your family never owned property or left a will; check the indexes a=\nnd=C2=A0you may be pleasantly surprised. Some people who never owned a home=\n have left very detailed wills disposing of their personal property.</p>=0A=\n</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Military records</strong> are available thr=\nough the<a href=3D\"http://www.archives.gov/veterans/\" target=3D\"_blank\"> Na=\ntional Archives</a>. Even if your ancestor never served in the military he =\nor she may have left a record. Military records can give very detailed info=\nrmation about a person including medical details and physical appearance, i=\nn addition to a record of his or her military career. Additionally, a wealt=\nh of information may be found regarding the widows and/or surviving childre=\nn of deceased servicemen. If you know or suspect your ancestor was in the m=\nilitary, or had registered for a draft, be sure to check for his or her=C2=\n=A0records.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Social Security Death Ind=\nex</strong>=C2=A0is available free <a href=3D\"http://ssdi.rootsweb.ancestry=\n.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\">online</a>. This is an excellent source for inform=\nation on twentieth-century ancestors. The online index for the most part ha=\ns information beginning about 1964. By applying for a copy of the deceased=\n=E2=80=99s original application, you will obtain information on the applica=\nnt=E2=80=99s place of birth, parents=E2=80=99 full names, and exact birth d=\nate.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Immigration Records:</strong> Ne=\nw York was a major immigration port in the United States for much of the ni=\nneteenth and into the twentieth=C2=A0centuries. These records may show the =\nname, spouse if present, traveling companion, marital status, year of birth=\n, departure port, and others depending on the city of arrival. Many immigra=\ntion records can be accessed online, through <a href=3D\"http://stevemorse.o=\nrg/\" target=3D\"_blank\">SteveMorse.org</a>=C2=A0and <a href=3D\"http://ellisi=\nsland.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\">EllisIsland.org </a>for a start.</p>=0A</li>=\n=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>Newspapers:</strong> Local papers can provide in=\nformation on marriages, deaths, team sports, organizations and their member=\ns, shows, arrests, and tragedies (fires, accidents, crimes). Many newspaper=\ns may be accessed online, often for a small fee. Early American Newspapers =\nSeries I is available with a membership to the NYG&amp;B. Others are found =\nonly in site specific libraries and archives. Among others, the New York Ti=\nmes can be searched back to 1851 <a href=3D\"http://query.nytimes.com/search=\n/\" target=3D\"_blank\">here</a>=C2=A0and the<a href=3D\"http://www.loc.gov/ind=\nex.html\" target=3D\"_blank\"> Library of Congress</a> has extensive newspaper=\n archives.=C2=A0 <a href=3D\"http://www.genealogybank.com/gbnk/\" target=3D\"_=\nblank\">Genealogy Bank</a> boasts coverage of over 4,500 newspapers in all 5=\n0 states; and<a href=3D\"http://www.onlinenewspapers.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\"=\n> Online Newspapers </a>provides links to newspapers worldwide.=C2=A0 A gui=\nde to newspapers in New York State that are on line is in the members secti=\non of this website. If you are logged-in as a member, click <a href=3D\"/new=\nspaper-guide\" target=3D\"_blank\">here</a> to see this guide.</p>=0A</li>=0A<=\nli>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<strong>The Milstein Division of the New York Public Library=\n</strong> maintains a very extensive collection of published genealogies an=\nd manuscripts.=C2=A0Their catalog is available through their <a href=3D\"htt=\np://www.nypl.org/locations/schwarzman/milstein-division-us-history-local-hi=\nstory-genealogy\" target=3D\"_blank\">website</a>. Although they may provide a=\n great deal of information, many published genealogies, especially older on=\nes (from the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries) can contain man=\ny errors. If there are no citations as to where the information was found, =\nyou will need to corroborate before incorporating data into your family his=\ntory.</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><h3>=0A\tAdditional Internet Resources</h3>=0A<ul><=\nli>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.americanancestors.org/home.html\" targe=\nt=3D\"_blank\"><strong>New England Historic Genealogical Society</strong></a>=\n is accessible to members. NEHGS provides a large, professionally staffed l=\nibrary in their Boston, Massachusetts, headquarters.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<=\np>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.archives.nysed.gov/aindex.shtml\" target=3D\"_b=\nlank\"><strong>The New York State Archives</strong></a> in Albany is a prima=\nry repository for records of New York=E2=80=99s counties and cities, not in=\ncluding New York City.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.=\ncyndislist.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>Cyndi=E2=80=99s List </strong></=\na>is an organized catalog of websites linking you to all kinds of informati=\non of use to family historians. The website is free.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<=\np>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.dar.org/library/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>D=\naughters of the American Revolution Library</strong></a>, Washington, DC=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.ellisisland.o=\nrg/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>Ellis Island</strong></a> was the federal go=\nvernment=E2=80=99s busiest port of immigrant traffic. The website contains =\nrecords of immigrant entries into New York harbor, plus all the ships that =\nentered the port of New York 1892-1924.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a hr=\nef=3D\"http://familytreemagazine.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>FamilyTree =\nMagazine</strong></a> produces an annual guide to the top <a href=3D\"http:/=\n/familytreemagazine.com/article/101-Best-Websites-2010\" target=3D\"_blank\"><=\nem>101 Best Websites</em></a>.=C2=A0 The most recent list published in July=\n 2010 focused specifically on the best free genealogy websites.=C2=A0</p>=\n=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.findagrave.com/\" target=3D=\n\"_blank\"><strong>The </strong></a><strong><a href=3D\"http://www.findagrave.=\ncom/\" target=3D\"_blank\">Find a Grave</a></strong><a href=3D\"http://www.find=\nagrave.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong> site</strong></a> is free and is us=\ner generated. It boasts many millions of burial records.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.genealogyintime.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><=\nem><strong>Genealogy In Time=E2=84=A2</strong></em></a> is a popular online=\n genealogy magazine that maintains the most complete collection on the inte=\nrnet of new genealogy record sets from around the world.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.genealogycenter.org/Home.aspx\" target=3D\"=\n_blank\"><strong>The Allen County Public Library</strong></a>, Fort Wayne, I=\nndiana, has one of the country=E2=80=99s premier genealogical collections. =\nThe library produces PERSI (PERiodical Source Index) which is of exceptiona=\nl value to researchers. =C2=A0This index to many thousands of genealogical =\narticles is available at the library itself and from local libraries with s=\nubscriptions.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.google.co=\nm\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>Google=E2=80=99s</strong></a> familiar website=\n can give you access to newspaper content and millions of books. Some data =\nthat you find will be free; other data will require payment.</p>=0A</li>=0A=\n<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.nysl.nysed.gov/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><s=\ntrong>The New York State Library</strong></a> in Albany, collects, preserve=\ns, and makes available materials that support State government work and doc=\nument State history.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.ra=\nogk.org/index.html\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>Random Acts of Genealogical K=\nindness</strong></a> (RAOGK) was established in 1999 as a free resource for=\n networking among researchers.=C2=A0 With volunteers in every U.S. state an=\nd many international locations RAOGK links researchers who need documents f=\nrom a distant location with others able to obtain them.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.usgenweb.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>=\nUSgenweb</strong></a> and <a href=3D\"http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/\" tar=\nget=3D\"_blank\"><strong>Rootsweb</strong></a> are two sites that help you at=\n the local level. They are created and maintained by volunteers and are of =\nuneven quality. They can be goldmines if you are lucky.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\tThe website of <strong><a href=3D\"http://www.stevemorse.org\">St=\nephen P. Morse</a></strong> offers alternative ways to access genealogy res=\nources on numerous other websites, plus original databases and programs tha=\nt facilitate doing genealogical research.=C2=A0 His website is especially r=\nich in material relating to Immigration and Census records.</p>=0A</li>=0A<=\n/ul><div>=0A\t<em>This is not a comprehensive list. Depending on your field =\nof study, there may be hundreds of other helpful sites available.</em> <em>=\nSee Cyndi's List above.</em></div>=0A<h3>=0A\tGenealogy Blogs</h3>=0A<div>=\n=0A\tThere are hundreds of family history blogs on the internet which provid=\ne free and often useful information to help you with your research.=C2=A0 F=\namily Tree Magazine produces an annual guide to the top 40 blogs recommende=\nd by its editors and its readers.=C2=A0 Click <a href=3D\"http://www.familyt=\nreemagazine.com/article/fab-forty\" target=3D\"_blank\">here</a> to read Famil=\ny Tree=E2=80=99s Fab Forty from May 2010; their next update will be publish=\ned in July 2011.=C2=A0 Here is a small sampling of blogs and free online ma=\ngazines that offer consistently high quality information and news about gen=\nealogy.</div>=0A<ul><li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://blog.eogn.com/\" targe=\nt=3D\"_blank\"><strong>Eastman=E2=80=99s Online Genealogy Newsletter</strong>=\n</a>:=C2=A0Said to be the most popular online genealogy magazine in the wor=\nld, Dick Eastman=E2=80=99s blog offers frequent postings on genealogy news =\nand events and the very latest information on technology for genealogy.</p>=\n=0A</li>=0A<li>=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://blog.familytreemagazine.com/in=\nsider/\" target=3D\"_blank\"><strong>Genealogy Insider:</strong></a>=C2=A0Brou=\nght to you by Diane Haddad and Family Tree Magazine staff, the Genealogy In=\nsider offers frequent postings on news, events, and resources plus useful l=\ninks and RSS feeds that let you track numerous topics.</p>=0A</li>=0A<li>=\n=0A<p>=0A\t\t\t<a href=3D\"http://www.genealogyintime.com/index.html\" target=3D=\n\"_blank\"><strong>Genealogy In Time=E2=84=A2:</strong></a>=C2=A0GenealogyInT=\nime=E2=84=A2 provides useful search engines, listings of the latest genealo=\ngy records, in-depth articles and other helpful resources.=C2=A0 It maintai=\nns the most complete collection on the internet of new genealogy record set=\ns from around the world.=C2=A0 In May 2011 they introduced a Genealogy Blog=\n Reader tool which, every five minutes, will automatically stream the lates=\nt genealogy blog postings to you from the internet.</p>=0A</li>=0A</ul><h3>=\n=0A\tUpgrade Your Research Skills</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tPurchase or borrow from a =\nlibrary a book about getting started in genealogy. Many such books exist. T=\nhe NYG&amp;B recommends Megan Smolenyak=E2=80=99s Who Do You Think You Are?=\n The Essential Guide to Tracing your Family History, Viking, 2009.</div>=0A=\n<h3>=0A\tJoin the Genealogical Community</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tLook for genealogic=\nal societies in your community and take advantage of their programs and the=\n expertise of their members to learn about research techniques and resource=\ns relevant to your project. Possibly the best advantage in joining a geneal=\nogical society is the networking possibilities: meeting others who have run=\n into the same problems you have and solved them, or finding someone who is=\n researching the same lines as you.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tLarger, regi=\nonal genealogical societies such as the NYG&amp;B=C2=A0and the <a href=3D\"h=\nttp://www.americanancestors.org/home.html\" target=3D\"_blank\">New England Hi=\nstoric Genealogical Society</a>=C2=A0offer extensive educational programs a=\nnd other learning opportunities.</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tYou might also =\nconsider attending a regional or national genealogical conference. These in=\nclude events produced by the <a href=3D\"http://www.ngsgenealogy.org/\" targe=\nt=3D\"_blank\">National Genealogical Society</a>=C2=A0and the <a href=3D\"http=\n://www.fgs.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\">Federation of Genealogical Societies</a>=\n. <a href=3D\"http://www.nergc.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\">The New England Regio=\nnal Genealogical Conference</a>=C2=A0is an example of a more focused confer=\nence. At these multi-day conferences, there will be dozens of 60 to 90 minu=\nte tutorials each day on a broad array of topics, taught by experts, for bo=\nth the beginner and the experienced researcher. In addition, many societies=\n and companies exhibit their wares in a trade-show format and are happy to =\nexplain their products and benefits.</div>=0A<h3>=0A\tWorking with Consultan=\nts</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tSome researchers may want to subcontract some of their r=\nesearch to consultants. The best way to find a consultant in your area, or =\nin the area where relevant records are held, or in the area of expertise yo=\nu seek (e.g. Irish research) is to visit the websites of the <a href=3D\"htt=\np://www.apgen.org/\" target=3D\"_blank\">Association of Professional Genealogi=\nsts</a>=C2=A0and the <a href=3D\"http://www.bcgcertification.org/\" target=3D=\n\"_blank\">Board for Certification of Genealogists</a>. The NYG&amp;B also ma=\nintains a <a href=3D\"/professional-genealogists\">list of researchers</a>, m=\nany of whom specialize in New York research.</div>=0A<h3>=0A\tBeyond the Bas=\nics</h3>=0A<div>=0A\tBy the time you have collected your own data, interview=\ned family members, familiarized yourself with the databases and sources men=\ntioned here, installed genealogical software, explored online library catal=\nogs, and joined a local or regional genealogical group, you will have uncov=\nered resources so vast and exciting that you won=E2=80=99t need further gui=\ndance from a =E2=80=9Cgetting started=E2=80=9D article like this one!</div>=\n=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A<p>=0A\t\t<span st=\nyle=3D\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\">=C2=A9 2011</span> The New=\n York Genealogical and Biographical Society. All rights reserved.</p>=0A</d=\niv>=0A<p>=0A\t=C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=\n=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <foot=\ner>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Priva=\ncy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of Service</a>=\n</li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a></li>=0A     =\n     <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"=\nhttp://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a =\nhref=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogical-Biographica=\nl-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"=\n/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebo=\nok page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#=\n!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/al=\nl/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  b=\norder=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/ny=\ngbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nyg=\nbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" />=\n</a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        New York Geneal=\nogical &amp; Professional Genealogical Researchers           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A      =\n            <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-sy=\nstem-main\" class=3D\"block =0A      =0A  =\n=0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=\n=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/295\" title=\n=3D\"Display a typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newy=\norkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"P=\nrinter-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-frien=\ndly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type=\n-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div clas=\ns=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><h2>There are many good =\nreasons to seek professional assistance in a family history research projec=\nt. The NYG&amp;B maintains a list of professional genealogists who have agr=\need to have their names, credentials, areas of specialty, and contact infor=\nmation listed here.</h2>=0A<h3>Working with a Professional</h3>=0A<div>Afte=\nr contacting a researcher, we recommend that you and the professional have =\na clear understanding, in writing, of what work will be undertaken, how it =\nwill be scheduled, whether there is an hourly or an all-inclusive charge fo=\nr services, who is responsible for travel, photocopy, telephone calls, etc.=\n, the total estimated cost of each stage of the undertaking, and at what in=\ntervals the researcher will report to and bill you.</div>=0A<div>=C2=A0</di=\nv>=0A<div>Please note that included on the list are persons or organization=\ns who are advertisers in The New York Genealogical and Biographical Record =\nor The New York Researcher. While we would not intentionally include anyone=\n on the list who we know to be unqualified, hiring a consultant entails som=\ne risk connected to challenges of your research and the capabilities of the=\n individual you hire. The NYG&amp;B cannot guarantee the quality or timelin=\ness of the work you will receive. =C2=A0</div>=0A<h3>Researchers Located in=\n the United States (Listed Alphabetically)</h3>=0A<p><strong>Mark Adams</st=\nrong></p>=0A<p>Specializes in record searching in New York City and suburbs=\n, including house and building histories.<br /> 209 Lincoln Place, Apt. 5D,=\n Brooklyn, NY 11217<br /> 718-789-8279<br /><br /><strong>Cornelia Wendell =\nBush, FSA Scotland</strong></p>=0A<p>Specializes in Colonial America, Engli=\nsh and Scottish ancestry, Heraldry and Coats of Arms, Lineage Societies.<br=\n /> PO Box 854, Warwick, NY 10990-0854<br /> skype id: corneliabush; 845-91=\n5-4160<br /><a href=3D\"http://corneliabush.blogspot.com/\" target=3D\"_blank\"=\n>http://corneliabush.blogspot.com/</a><br /> website: <a href=3D\"http://www=\n.corneliabush.com\" target=3D\"_blank\">www.corneliabush.com</a><br /><br /><s=\ntrong>Sharon DeBartolo Carmack, CG, MFA in Narrative Nonfiction Writing</st=\nrong></p>=0A<p>Warren, Carmack &amp; Associates<br />358 South 700 East, #6=\n03, Salt Lake City, UT 84102<br />Specializes in genealogical literary serv=\nices and publishing: writing, mentoring, and editing of family histories, m=\nemoirs, biographies; book layout, design, indexing, publishing, and order f=\nulfillment; also U.S., Irish, and Italian research.<br />Cell: 719-660-8445=\n<br />email:=C2=A0<a href=3D\"mailto:sdcarmack@gmail.com\">sdcarmack@gmail.co=\nm</a><br /><a href=3D\"mailto:sdcarmack@gmail.com\"></a>website: <a href=3D\"h=\nttp://www.warrencarmack.com\" target=3D\"_blank\">www.warrencarmack.com</a></p>=\n=0A<p><strong>Laura H. Congleton</strong></p>=0A<p>Specializes in military =\nhistory, lineage societies, NYC (especially Brooklyn), vital records, proba=\nte, land records, and naturalizations. =\n <div id=3D\"node-473\" class=3D\"node node-page clearfix\" about=3D\"/nyplsearc=\nh\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"conten=\nt\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"=\nhttp://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/473\" title=3D\"Display a printer-frien=\ndly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this=\n.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-=\nmargin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/=\nall/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" ti=\ntle=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></spa=\nn><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-la=\nbel-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" prope=\nrty=3D\"content:encoded\"><h2>=0A\tAll items donated by the New York Genealogi=\ncal and Biographical Society to the New York Public Library may be found at=\n its Stephen A. Schwarzman Building, which is located at Fifth Avenue and 4=\n2nd Street in New York City.=C2=A0 Much of the collection may be found in t=\nhe Irma and Paul Milstein Division of United States History, Local History =\nand Genealogy, Room 121; other portions may be found in the Microforms Sect=\nion, Room 100; the Map Division, Room 117; and the Manuscript Division, Roo=\nm 328.=C2=A0</h2>=0A<h3>=0A\tPlease note that some material is stored offsit=\ne and, therefore, may not be immediately available; these items will be ide=\nntified in the Catalog as \"Offsite-Request in Advance.\" To submit a request=\n in advance, send an email to <a href=3D\"mailto:histref@nypl.org\">histref@n=\nypl.org</a>.</h3>=0A<h4>=0A\t=C2=A0</h4>=0A<h4>=0A\t<u>Search the NYPL Catalo=\ng</u></h4>=0A<div>=0A\tAll NYG&amp;B materials have been added to the Librar=\ny=E2=80=99s online Catalog at <a href=3D\"http://catalog.nypl.org/search\">ht=\ntp://catalog.nypl.org/search</a></div>=0A<div>=0A\tIn the Catalog, you can s=\nearch by Keyword, if title is not known, or by exact Title or Author.=C2=A0=\n</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tSubject heading searches can be u=\nseful and a bit more focused.=C2=A0 For example, if you are looking for fam=\nily histories, try a Subject search for: <em>surname family</em></div>=0A<d=\niv>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 <em>example</em>: Bacon Family</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=\n=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tFor location, try a Subject search for: <em>locatio=\nn</em></div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 <em>example</em>: Rockland County N=\n.Y. Genealogy</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Buffalo N.Y. Genealo=\ngy</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 =C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 New Jersey Genealogy</div>=0A<di=\nv>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tHowever, Keyword searching can work just fine=\n too.=C2=A0 There is also an Advanced Search option on the left-hand menu w=\nhich allows you to narrow your search to a particular kind of material (e.g=\n. book, manuscript, microform, etc.)=C2=A0 Additional details, especially f=\nor manuscript-type materials, can also be searched at \"Find Archival Materi=\nals\": =C2=A0<a href=3D\"http://www.nypl.org/find-archival-materials\">http://=\nwww.nypl.org/find-archival-materials</a></div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<h=\n4>=0A\t<u>Find NYG&amp;B Titles</u></h4>=0A<div>=0A\tTitles donated by the NY=\nG&amp;B retain =E2=80=9CNYGB=E2=80=9D as part of their call numbers.=C2=A0 =\nFor example, you can search <a href=3D\"http://catalog.nypl.org/search%7ES1/=\n?searchtype=3Dc&amp;searcharg=3Dnygb+map&amp;searchscope=3D1&amp;SORT=3DD&a=\nmp;extended=3D1&amp;searchlimits=3D&amp;searchorigarg=3Dcnygb+man\">NYGB Map=\n</a> to see all the NYGB maps in the Map Division, or<a href=3D\"http://cata=\nlog.nypl.org/search%7ES1/?searchtype=3Dc&amp;searcharg=3DNYGB+coll&amp;sear=\nchscope=3D1&amp;sortdropdown=3D-&amp;SORT=3DD&amp;extended=3D1&amp;searchli=\nmits=3D&amp;searchorigarg=3DcMssCol+NYGB\"> NYGB Coll</a> to search a geneal=\nogist's papers.=C2=A0=C2=A0 Manuscripts follow a different convention: <a h=\nref=3D\"http://catalog.nypl.org/search%7ES1/?searchtype=3Dc&amp;searcharg=3D=\nMssCol+NYGB&amp;searchscope=3D1&amp;sortdropdown=3D-&amp;SORT=3DD&amp;exten=\nded=3D1&amp;SUBMIT=3DSearch&amp;searchlimits=3D&amp;searchorigarg=3DcMssCol=\n+NYGB\">MssCol NYGB</a>.=C2=A0=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=\n=0A\tWhile items from the collection list the New York Genealogical and Biog=\nraphical Society Collection as an additional author, it is not possible to =\nobtain a complete list of NYG&amp;B titles from the NYPL Catalog through a =\nsearch on Author because the NYPL Catalog has a search result limit of 32,0=\n00.=C2=A0</div>=0A<h4>=0A\t=C2=A0</h4>=0A<h3>=0A\t<strong>Get Help</strong>:=\n=C2=A0 If you are unable to find an item that you believe should be in the =\nNYPL catalog, please contact the staff of the Milstein Division at <a href=\n=3D\"mailto:histref@nypl.org\">histref@nypl.org</a> or 212-930-0828.</h3>=0A<=\n/div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A         <h1 class=\n=3D\"title\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      Images           \t\t</=\nh1>=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A =\n   <div  =0A   =\n             =0A      </aside>=0A            <article class=3D\"\">      =0A =\n               =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A       =\n               The New York Genealogical and Biographical Society Elects Tw=\no New Fellows: Suzanne McVetty and Meldon J. Wolfgang III.           \t\t</h1>=\n=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    =\n<div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <=\ndiv class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-492\" class=3D\"node node-press-=\nrelease clearfix\" about=3D\"/node/492\" typeof=3D\"sioc:Item foaf:Document\">=\n=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"pri=\nnt-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.=\norg/print/492\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of this page.\" c=\nlass=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return false\" rel=3D=\n\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image=\n\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons/prin=\nt_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly vers=\nion\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-=\nname-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"fi=\neld-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><p>=\n=C2=A0</p>=0A<p><strong>November 15, 2011. </strong>The New York Genealogic=\nal and Biographical Society announces the election of two leading New York =\ngenealogists as Fellows of the Genealogical and Biographical Society (FGBS)=\n.</p>=0A<p>The designation of Fellow of the Genealogical and Biographical S=\nociety, the oldest such designation in the genealogical field in the nation=\n, is reserved for people who have contributed to New York genealogical rese=\narch, writing, speaking, and advocacy at the highest level of proficiency. =\nThere are currently fourteen Fellows.</p>=0A<p><strong>Suzanne McVetty</str=\nong>, who became a Certified Genealogist in 1987, has been researching and =\nwriting family histories for over twenty-five years. She specializes in New=\n York City and Long Island subjects. She also has experience searching for =\nmissing heirs in partnership with trusts and estates attorneys. She has wri=\ntten articles for leading genealogical publications, has written research g=\nuides for the New York Researcher and the Society=E2=80=99s website, and ha=\ns spoken at many regional and national genealogical conferences. Her topics=\n include <em>Using Land Records in Genealogical Research, Using Probate Rec=\nords in Genealogical Research; Bright Lights- Urban Research; and Vital Rec=\nords: Building Blocks of Genealogical Research</em>.</p>=0A<p>She has serve=\nd as president of the Genealogical Speakers Guild, treasurer of the Associa=\ntion of Professional Genealogists, a volunteer at the National Archives Nor=\ntheast Region, and for over twenty years was chairperson of the Nassau Gene=\nalogy Workshop. For 16 years she has served on the Education Committee of t=\nhe NYG&amp;B and regularly serves as an expert consultant at Society progra=\nms, including the biennial =E2=80=9CResearch in Albany=E2=80=9D program.</p>=\n=0A<p><strong>Meldon J. Wolfgang III</strong> is a native of Albany, NY, an=\nd the founder-owner of Jonathan Sheppard Books. Mr. Wolfgang has been a gen=\nealogist since the 1960s and has a national reputation as a scholar and spe=\naker on a wide range of genealogical topics. He has published articles on f=\namily history in national publications, and since 2005 he has written the g=\nenealogy column for <em>New York Archives</em>, the quarterly publication o=\nf the New York State Archives Partnership Trust. His wide-range of speaking=\n topics includes <em>Uncommon Research Tools; Deconstructing City Directori=\nes; Using Archival Collections in the 21st Century; Beyond the Basics for U=\nsing Newspapers in Genealogical Research; Prosopography, Cluster Studies, a=\nnd Record Linkage Techniques; Tracing German Ancestors in Europe; Germans a=\nnd German-Americans in 19th Century America; and Using Maps in Genealogical=\n Research</em>.</p>=0A<p>He served as Commissioner of Human Resources for t=\nhe city of Albany, a member of the Albany Historic Sites Commission and a T=\nrustee of the Albany County Historical Society. He also served as a trustee=\n of the Albany Public Library, was president of the Upper Hudson Library Sy=\nstem and was one of the original appointed trustees of the joint Albany Cit=\ny-County Archives.</p>=0A<p>Mr. Wolfgang received his undergraduate degree =\nfrom McGill University in Montreal and completed further graduate study at =\nColumbia University. He serves on the Education Committee of the NYG&amp;B =\nand on the Advisory Board of the New York Family History School.</p>=0A<p><=\nstrong>About the NYG&amp;B</strong> The New York Genealogical and Biographi=\ncal Society has been the authoritative source for research on New York fami=\nlies and families with New York connections since 1869. By offering educati=\nonal programs, scholarly and informational publications, and online resourc=\nes, the New York Genealogical and Biographical Society helps people of all =\nbackgrounds build connections with their families and their communities, =\n=C2=AC especially those linked to New York City, State, and region =C2=AC a=\nnd to appreciate their families=E2=80=99 experience in the broader context =\nof American history. The NYG&amp;B maintains an eLibrary of digital materia=\nl, including the entire run of its quarterly scholarly journal <em>The NYG&=\namp;B Record</em>, for its members at <a href=3D\"http://www.newyorkfamilyhi=\nstory.org\">www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org</a>.</p>=0A<p>=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=C2=\n=A0</p>=0A<p><strong>Media Contact </strong></p>=0A<p>Cathy Michelsen</p>=\n=0A<p>212-755-8532, ext. 208=C2=A0</p>=0A<p><a href=3D\"mailto:cmichelsen@ny=\ngbs.org?subject=3DNYGBS%20FGBS%20Information\">cmichelsen@nygbs.org</a></p>=\n=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A =\n </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A    =\n    <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          =\n<li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a=\n href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/pre=\nss\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com=\n\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.faceb=\nook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/16649844337231=\n3\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/=\nimages/content-img/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /=\n></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=\n=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/=\ncontent-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A =\n           <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"=\n  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/=\nicon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A=\n     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp;         <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-sys=\ntem-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content=\n\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-463\" class=3D\"node node-press-release clearfix\" ab=\nout=3D\"/node/463\" typeof=3D\"sioc:Item foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =\n=0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type=\n-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div clas=\ns=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><div>=0A\t<strong>NEW YOR=\nK, NY, September 26, 2011.</strong> On Thursday, November 17th, the New Yor=\nk Genealogical and Biographical Society will present two advanced lectures =\non Irish Genealogy given by Donna Moughty, one of the leading authorities o=\nn the subject. =C2=A0=C2=A0Ms. Moughty will first address =E2=80=9CHow to L=\nocate Famine Emigrants Using Griffith=E2=80=99s Valuation,=E2=80=9D which w=\nas the first full-scale valuation of property in Ireland, published between=\n 1847 and 1864. =C2=A0In her second lecture she will discuss =E2=80=9CSourc=\nes for Irish Research=E2=80=9D and describe records that survived the destr=\nuction of the Irish Public Records Office in 1922, as well as other records=\n available in both Ireland and the United States. =C2=A0=0A<p>\tThe program =\nwill take place at the headquarters of the NYG&amp;B at 36 West 44th Street=\n, 7th Floor, between 5:30 and 8:30 pm, and will be accompanied by light ref=\nreshments. Registration is strictly limited: NYG&amp;B members $30; non-mem=\nbers $45. =C2=A0<a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.myshopify.com/collec=\ntions/events\">Register online</a>=C2=A0or call Lauren Maehrlein at 212-755-=\n8532, ext. 211.</p>=0A<p>\tThis event is part of an NYG&amp;B program track =\nwhich provides research assistance specific to various ethnicities which ar=\ne heavily represented among New Yorkers. =C2=A0A full-day program on =E2=80=\n=9CBritish Islands Research=E2=80=9D took place in the spring; a lecture on=\n =E2=80=9CNew Avenues to Italian Family Research=E2=80=9D took place earlie=\nr in September. =C2=A0Upcoming lectures include =E2=80=9CThe Road Less Trav=\neled: Polish &amp; Ukrainian Research=E2=80=9D on November 9th. =C2=A0Ms. M=\noughty will also present a free, introductory lecture on Irish genealogy on=\n November 16th at the New York Public Library, which is co-sponsored by the=\n NYG&amp;B and the NYPL. =C2=A0</p>=0A<p>\tDonna Moughty, a professional gen=\nealogist and former regional manager for a national technology company, tea=\nches classes on a variety of subjects including Internet, Irish research, a=\nnd computer topics.=C2=A0 She attended the National Institute for Genealogi=\ncal Research at the National Archives, the Third and Fourth Irish Genealogi=\ncal Congress in Ireland, the Salt Lake Institute =E2=80=93 Irish Research, =\nand the Institute for Genealogy and Historical Research at Samford Universi=\nty.=C2=A0 Based in Florida, she is a member of the Association of Professio=\nnal Genealogists; Treasurer of the Genealogical Speakers Guild; and a Deleg=\nate to the Federation of Genealogical Societies. =C2=A0</p>=0A<p>\t<strong>A=\nbout the NYG&amp;B</strong></p></div>=0A<div>=0A\t<br />=0A\tThe New York Gen=\nealogical and Biographical Society has been a primary resource for research=\n on New York families since 1869. =C2=A0By offering educational programs, s=\ncholarly and informational publications, and online resources, the New York=\n Genealogical and Biographical Society helps people of all backgrounds buil=\nd connections with their families and their communities, =C2=A0=C2=A0especi=\nally those linked to New York City, State, and region =C2=A0=C2=A0and to ap=\npreciate their families=E2=80=99 experience in the broader context of Ameri=\ncan history. =C2=A0The NYG&amp;B maintains an eLibrary of digital material,=\n including the entire run of its quarterly scholarly journal <em>The NYG&am=\np;B Record</em>, for its members on its website, <a href=3D\"http://www.newy=\norkfamilyhistory.org\">newyorkfamilyhistory.org.</a></div>=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>=\nMedia Contact</strong></p>=0A<div>=0A\tCathy Michelsen</div>=0A<div>=0A\t212-=\n755-8532, ext. 208;=C2=A0<a href=3D\"mailto:cmichelsen@nygbs.org\">cmichelsen=\n@nygbs.org</a></div>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A =\n                    =\n  Prof. Henry Louis Gates, Jr. Elected to NYG&amp;B Board of Trustees      =\n     \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region region-cont=\nent\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=\n=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-194\" class=3D\"nod=\ne node-press-release clearfix\" about=3D\"/node/194\" typeof=3D\"sioc:Item foaf=\n:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span c=\nlass=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfam=\nilyhistory.org/print/194\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of th=\nis page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return fa=\nlse\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D=\n\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print=\n/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-fr=\niendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"f=\nield field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div =\nclass=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:en=\ncoded\"><p>=0A\t<b>NEW YORK, NY. September 13, 2011.</b>=C2=A0 W. Francis Pri=\nce, Jr., chairman of the New York Genealogical and Biographical Society, an=\nnounced today that Prof. Henry Louis Gates, Jr. has been elected to the org=\nanization=E2=80=99s Board of Trustees.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tProf. Gates is the Alph=\nonse Fletcher University Professor at Harvard University and director of th=\ne W.E.B. Du Bois Institute for African and African American Research at Har=\nvard. His most recent book, <em>Faces of America</em> (New York University =\nPress, 2010), expands on interviews he conducted for his critically acclaim=\ned PBS documentary series of the same name.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tMr. Price said, =\n=E2=80=9CProf. Gates=E2=80=99 credentials as a professor, scholar, literary=\n critic, filmmaker, and author are extraordinarily extensive.=C2=A0 A menti=\non that he was a MacArthur Fellow barely even scratches the surface. We ele=\ncted him to the Board, and he accepted the appointment, because of his deep=\n and longstanding interest in genealogy and family history. His contributio=\nns to this field are simply staggering.=E2=80=9D</p>=0A<p>=0A\tProf. Gates i=\ns one of the preeminent leaders in the field of genealogy, including geneti=\ncs-based research, of which he is a pioneer; biography; and family history.=\n=C2=A0 Prof. Gates is Editor-in-Chief of the Oxford African American Studie=\ns Center, a scholarly online resource in African American and Africana Stud=\nies. He is also Editor-in-Chief of The Root, an online news magazine that c=\novers African American genealogy, among other subjects, and co-editor of th=\ne African American National Biography, an eight-volume work.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tP=\nrof. Gates has been developing programming for PBS since 1995. In 2006, he =\nproduced his first family history series, =E2=80=9CAfrican American Lives,=\n=E2=80=9D and the second series aired in 2008.=C2=A0 =E2=80=9CFaces of Amer=\nica,=E2=80=9D a third series, aired in 2010. That program examined the gene=\nalogy of Stephen Colbert, Queen Noor, Meryl Streep, Yo-Yo Ma, and eight oth=\ners.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tHe is the author of <em>Finding Oprah=E2=80=99s Roots, Fi=\nnding Your Own</em> (Crown, 2007), a meditation on genetics, genealogy, and=\n race. He wrote <em>In S</em>ear<em>ch of Our Roots</em> (Crown 2009), the =\ncompanion book to his PBS documentary series, =E2=80=9CAfrican American Liv=\nes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0 <em>Faces of America</em> (New York University Pre=\nss, 2010) is the companion book to the 2010 series.=C2=A0 A fourth series i=\ns in production. NYG&amp;B staff assisted with original research of a subje=\nct, a celebrity Hollywood couple with impressive family histories.</p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\tProf. Gates is at his most persuasive when he is speaking about the rol=\ne genealogy can play in=C2=A0 stimulating learning, building self-identity,=\n and understanding the importance of history. In the introduction to his bo=\nok <em>Faces of America</em>, he said, =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6 the secret of gen=\nealogy is that every family story, no matter how seemingly insignificant, a=\nnd the name and identity of each of our ancestors, no matter how seemingly =\nunremarkable her or his life, contain an abundance of revelations, both abo=\nut them and about ourselves.=E2=80=9D</p>=0A<p>=0A\tHe has been actively res=\nearching his own family. And, in 2006, he was inducted into the Sons of the=\n American Revolution after tracing his lineage back to John Redman, a free =\nblack man who fought in the Revolutionary War.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tProf. Gates is =\nactively involved in other institutions in New York City sharing the NYG&am=\np;B=E2=80=99s interest in the history of New York families. He sits on the =\nboard of the New York Public Library, to which the NYG&amp;B recently gave =\nits research collections, and the New-York Historical Society.</p>=0A<p>=0A=\n\t<strong>About the NYG&amp;B</strong></p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe New York Genealogica=\nl and Biographical Society has been a primary resource for research on New =\nYork families since 1869. =C2=A0The NYG&amp;B seeks to advance genealogical=\n scholarship and enhance the capabilities of both new and experienced resea=\nrchers of family history through a rich schedule of programs, workshops, an=\nd repository tours; through its quarterly scholarly journal <em>The Record =\n</em>and its quarterly review <em>The New York Researcher</em>; and through=\n an eLibrary of unique digital material on its website <a href=3D\"http://ww=\nw.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/\">www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org</a>.</p>=0A<div>=\n=0A\t<strong>Media Contact</strong></div>=0A<div>=0A\tMcKelden Smith</div>=0A=\n<div>=0A\t212-755-8532, ext. 204; <a href=3D\"mailto:msmith@nygbs.org\">msmith=\n@nygbs.org</a></div>=0A<p>=0A\t=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=0A\t=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=0A\t=C2=\n=A0</p>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</d=\niv>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=\n=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A   =\n       <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A         =\n <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=\n=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironp=\naper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://w=\nww.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/166498=\n443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/theme=\ns/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=\n=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistor=\ny\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/i=\nmages/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></=\na>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nof=\nollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/conten=\nt-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </n=\nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp; =0A                =0A         <h1 class=3D\"titl=\ne\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      A Day-Long Program on Cutting=\n-Edge Genealogy, Saturday, September 24           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A     =\n             <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-s=\nystem-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"conte=\nnt\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-383\" class=3D\"node node-press-release clearfix\" =\nabout=3D\"/pressreleasecuttingedge\" typeof=3D\"sioc:Item foaf:Document\">=0A=\n=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-=\nlink\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org=\n/print/383\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of this page.\" clas=\ns=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return false\" rel=3D\"no=\nfollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" s=\nrc=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons/print_i=\ncon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version=\n\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-nam=\ne-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field=\n-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><p>=0A\t=\n<strong>NEW YORK, NY, August 15, 2011</strong><strong>. </strong>On Saturda=\ny, September 24th, the New York Genealogical and Biographical Society will =\npresent Dick Eastman, Ruth A. Carr, and David Kleiman in a full-day program=\n designed to enhance your online genealogical searches.=C2=A0 The program w=\nill take place in the South Court Auditorium of the New York Public Library=\n=E2=80=99s Stephen A. Schwarzman Building, Fifth Avenue at 42nd Street, New=\n York, NY.=C2=A0</p>=0A<p>=0A\tDick Eastman is the publisher of =E2=80=9CEas=\ntman's Online Genealogy Newsletter,=E2=80=9D the daily genealogy technology=\n newsletter with more than 60,000 readers worldwide.=C2=A0 He will deliver =\ntwo lectures: <em>Genealogy Searches on Google: Extract the Most Genealogic=\nal Information Possible from Everyone's Favorite Search Engine</em> and <em=\n>The Latest Technology for Genealogists: An In-Depth Look at Today's Techno=\nlogy.</em></p>=0A<p>=0A\tRuth A. Carr retired in 2008 as Chief of the Irma a=\nnd Paul Milstein Division of United States History, Local History and Genea=\nlogy, New York Public Library where she worked for 20 years.=C2=A0 She will=\n present a talk on <em>Other Places Your Ancestors Might Be Hiding: =E2=80=\n=9CNon-Genealogy=E2=80=9D Databases and Internet Resources to Explore.</em>=\n</p>=0A<p>=0A\tA genealogist and family historian for over 35 years, David K=\nleiman co-founded and chairs the New York Computers and Genealogy Special I=\nnterest Group and serves on the executive council of the Jewish Genealogica=\nl Society, Inc. and on the Education Committee of the NYG&amp;B.=C2=A0 He w=\nill deliver two lectures: <em>Rediscovering the Globe: Maps Online, GIS, Go=\nogle Earth </em>and<em> Technology &amp; Design: Looking Good in Print and =\non the Screen.</em></p>=0A<p>=0A\tThe program begins at 9:30 a.m. at the NYP=\nL=E2=80=99s South Court Auditorium and will end at 5:00 pm; there will be a=\n break for lunch on-your-own.=C2=A0 Registration for NYG&amp;B members is $=\n60, non-members is $90.=C2=A0 <a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.myshop=\nify.com/collections/events\">Register online</a>.=C2=A0 For additional infor=\nmation, contact Lauren Maehrlein, Director of Education, at 212-755-8532, e=\nxt. 211, or by e-mailing <a href=3D\"mailto:education@nygbs.org\">education@n=\nygbs.org</a>.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>About the NYG&amp;B</strong></p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\tThe New York Genealogical and Biographical Society has been a primary r=\nesource for research on New York families since 1869. =C2=A0The NYG&amp;B s=\neeks to advance genealogical scholarship and enhance the capabilities of bo=\nth new and experienced researchers of family history through a rich schedul=\ne of programs, workshops, and repository tours; through its quarterly schol=\narly journal <em>The NYG&amp;B Record </em>and its quarterly review <em>The=\n New York Researcher</em>; and through an eLibrary of unique digital materi=\nal on its website <a href=3D\"http://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/\">www.newy=\norkfamilyhistory.org</a>.</p>=0A<p>=0A\t<strong>Media Contact</strong></p>=\n=0A<div>=0A\tCathy Michelsen</div>=0A<div>=0A\t212-755-8532, ext. 208; <a hre=\nf=3D\"mailto:cmichelsen@nygbs.org\">cmichelsen@nygbs.org</a></div>=0A<p>=0A\t=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div></div=\n>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </ar=\nticle>=0A    </div>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A         =\n <li><a href=3D\"/privacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/serv=\nice-terms\">Terms of Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertisin=\ng\">Advertising</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></=\nli>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=\n=0A        </ul>=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New=\n-York-Genealogical-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  =\ntarget=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/ic=\non-facebook.png\" alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <=\na href=3D\"http://twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D=\n\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitte=\nr.png\" alt=3D\"Twitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"h=\nttp://www.flickr.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><im=\ng src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D=\n\"Flickr page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyrig=\nht\">=0A        New York Genealogical &amp;     =0A                =0A      </aside>=0A            <arti=\ncle class=3D\"\">      =0A                =0A         <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=\n=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      Edward T. O=E2=80=99Donnell To Spe=\nak About New York Immigration           \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A               =\n   <div class=3D\"region region-content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main=\n\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A   =\n <div id=3D\"node-332\" class=3D\"node node-press-release clearfix\" about=3D\"/=\nnode/332\" typeof=3D\"sioc:Item foaf:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <di=\nv class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span class=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_=\nhtml\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/print/332\" title=3D\"Displa=\ny a printer-friendly version of this page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D=\n\"window.open(this.href); return false\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print=\n-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyh=\nistory.org/sites/all/modules/print/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-fri=\nendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" />Printer-friendly versio=\nn</a></span></span><div class=3D\"field field-name-body field-type-text-with=\n-summary field-label-hidden\"><div class=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field=\n-item even\" property=3D\"content:encoded\"><p>=0A\t<strong>NEW YORK, NY, April=\n 6, 2011</strong><strong>. </strong>On Wednesday, April 20th, the New York =\nGenealogical and Biographical Society and the New York Public Library will =\npresent historian and author Edward T. O=E2=80=99Donnell, Ph.D. in a lectur=\ne at the Library=E2=80=99s Stephen A. Schwarzman Building, Fifth Avenue at =\n42nd Street, New York, NY.=C2=A0 An expert on New York City history, Dr. O=\n=E2=80=99Donnell is an Associate Professor of History at Holy Cross College=\n in Worcester, MA.=C2=A0 His books include <u>Visions of America: A History=\n of the United States</u>, <u>Ship Ablaze: The Tragedy of the Steamboat Gen=\neral Slocum</u>, and <u>1001 Things Everyone Should Know About Irish Americ=\nan History</u>.=C2=A0</p>=0A<div>=0A\tIn this engaging multimedia presentati=\non, Dr. O=E2=80=99Donnell will explore how and why so many millions have co=\nme to the U.S. and what challenges this tradition has posed to national ide=\nntity, tolerance, and democracy. =C2=A0He will examine the major immigrant =\ngroups -- Irish, German, Italian, Jewish, and Chinese -- who arrived in the=\n 19<sup>th</sup> and early 20<sup>th</sup> centuries, the vibrant ethnic en=\nclaves they established, the struggles they endured to earn a living, and t=\nhe contributions they made to New York, the nation=E2=80=99s ultimate multi=\ncultural city. This talk addresses many aspects of the immigrant experience=\n, including tenement life, labor and the labor movement, and nativism.</div>=\n=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\tThe program begins at 5:30 pm in the NY=\nPL=E2=80=99s South Court Auditorium.=C2=A0 Reservations are not required; s=\neating is on a first-come, first-served basis.=C2=A0 For additional informa=\ntion, contact Lauren Maehrlein, Director of Education, at 212-755-8532, ext=\n. 211, or <a href=3D\"mailto:education@nygbs.org\">education@nygbs.org</a>.</=\ndiv>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0</div>=0A<div>=0A\t<strong>About the NYG&amp;B</strong=\n></div>=0A<p>=0A\tThe New York Genealogical and Biographical Society has bee=\nn a primary resource for research on New York families since 1869. =C2=A0By=\n offering educational programs, scholarly and informational publications, a=\nnd online resources, the New York Genealogical and Biographical Society hel=\nps people of all backgrounds build connections with their families and thei=\nr communities, =C2=AD especially those linked to New York City, State, and =\nregion =C2=AD and to appreciate their families=E2=80=99 experience in the b=\nroader context of American history. =C2=A0The NYG&amp;B maintains an eLibra=\nry of unique digital material, including the entire run of its quarterly sc=\nholarly journal <em>The NYG&amp;B Record, </em>for its members at <a href=\n=3D\"http://www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org/\">www.newyorkfamilyhistory.org</a>.=\n</p>=0A<div>=0A\t<strong>Media Contact</strong></div>=0A<div>=0A\tCathy Miche=\nlsen</div>=0A<div>=0A\t212-755-8532, ext. 208; <a href=3D\"mailto:cmichelsen@=\nnygbs.org\">cmichelsen@nygbs.org</a></div>=0A<div>=0A\t=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</div>=0A</div></div></div>  </div>=0A=0A  =\n=0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A      </article>=0A    </di=\nv>=0A    <footer>=0A      <nav>=0A        <ul>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/=\nprivacy\">Privacy</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/service-terms\">Terms =\nof Service</a></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/advertising\">Advertising</a=\n></li>=0A          <li><a href=3D\"/press\">Press Room</a></li>=0A          <=\nli><a href=3D\"http://www.ironpaper.com\">Web Design</a></li>=0A        </ul>=\n=0A        <a href=3D\"http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-New-York-Genealogic=\nal-Biographical-Society/166498443372313\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank=\n\"><img src=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-facebook.png\"=\n alt=3D\"Facebook page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http:/=\n/twitter.com/#!/nyfamilyhistory\" rel=3D\"nofollow\" target=3D\"_blank\"><img sr=\nc=3D\"/sites/all/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-twitter.png\" alt=3D\"Tw=\nitter page\"  border=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A            <a href=3D\"http://www.flickr=\n.com/photos/nygbs/\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"  target=3D\"_blank\"><img src=3D\"/sites/=\nall/themes/nygbs/images/content-img/icon-flickr.png\" alt=3D\"Flickr page\"  b=\norder=3D\"0\" /></a>=0A      </nav>=0A     <div id=3D\"copyright\">=0A        N=\new York Genealogical &amp; =0A                =0A =\n        <h1 class=3D\"title\" id=3D\"page-title\">=0A                      New =\nEditors Selected for The New York Genealogical and Biographical Record     =\n      \t\t</h1>=0A       =0A                  <div class=3D\"region region-con=\ntent\">=0A    <div id=3D\"block-system-main\" class=3D\"block block-system\">=0A=\n=0A    =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <div id=3D\"node-334\" class=3D\"nod=\ne node-press-release clearfix\" about=3D\"/node/334\" typeof=3D\"sioc:Item foaf=\n:Document\">=0A=0A  =0A      =0A  =0A  <div class=3D\"content\">=0A    <span c=\nlass=3D\"print-link\"><span class=3D\"print_html\"><a href=3D\"http://newyorkfam=\nilyhistory.org/print/334\" title=3D\"Display a printer-friendly version of th=\nis page.\" class=3D\"print-page\" onclick=3D\"window.open(this.href); return fa=\nlse\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"><img class=3D\"print-icon print-icon-margin\" typeof=3D=\n\"foaf:Image\" src=3D\"http://newyorkfamilyhistory.org/sites/all/modules/print=\n/icons/print_icon.gif\" alt=3D\"Printer-friendly version\" title=3D\"Printer-fr=\niendly version\" />Printer-friendly version</a></span></span><div class=3D\"f=\nield field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden\"><div =\nclass=3D\"field-items\"><div class=3D\"field-item even\" property=3D\"content:en=\ncoded\"><p>=0A\t<strong>NEW YORK, NY, December 22, 2010. </strong>The New Yor=\nk Genealogical and Biographical Society has selected Laura Murphy DeGrazia,=\n CG, and Karen Mauer Green as the new co-editors of The<em> New York Geneal=\nogical and Biographical Record</em>, replacing Patricia Law Hatcher who ret=\nired after completing the October 2010 issue.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tLaura Murphy DeG=\nrazia is currently the guest editor of the January issue of the <em>Record.=\n </em>Recently she completed a two-year term as president of the Board for =\nCertification of Genealogists, where she remains a trustee and a member of =\nthe Executive Committee.=C2=A0 Her articles and reviews have appeared in th=\ne <em>NYG&amp;B</em> <em>Record, </em>the<em> National Genealogical Society=\n Quarterly, </em>the<em> New England Historical and Genealogical Register</=\nem>, and other publications.=C2=A0 She holds a BA from Adelphi University, =\nwhere she was a Presidential Scholar, and an MA in Computer Science with ho=\nnors from Hofstra University. Ms. DeGrazia lives on Long Island.</p>=0A<p>=\n=0A\tInvolved in genealogy since 1977, Karen Mauer Green has written six boo=\nks, as well as numerous articles, columns, and reviews. In 1982 she founded=\n Frontier Press, a source for genealogical and historical books. She served=\n the Association of Professional Genealogists as board member and regional =\nvice-president, and the Federation of Genealogical Societies as board membe=\nr, national conference chair, vice-president for administration, and in num=\nerous other capacities. She has a BS in history with honors and an MA in Mu=\nseum Studies from the State University of New York at Oneonta. Ms. Green li=\nves in Cooperstown, N.Y.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tTheir selection was the result of a l=\nengthy national search directed by a committee that included former <em>Rec=\nord</em> editor Harry Macy Jr., FASG, FGBS and three current trustees of th=\ne NYG&amp;B: Anita Anderson Lustenberger, CG, FGBS; Elizabeth L. Bradley, P=\nh.D., Assistant Director for Public Programs and Lifelong Learning at the N=\new York Public Library; and Luke Ives Pontifell, founder and CEO of Thornwi=\nllow Press.</p>=0A<p>=0A\tMcKelden Smith, president of the NYG&amp;B, said, =\n=E2=80=9CThe search put me in touch with some of the leading genealogists i=\nn the country, who were enormously helpful on a very granular level.=C2=A0 =\nI was hugely gratified by the intense interest the leaders of the field hav=\ne in the future of the<em> Record</em>, and I am certain that Laura and Kar=\nen will have their support.=E2=80=9D</p>=0A<p>=0A\tHe said that an important=\n issue for scholars was that the standards of the<em> NYG&amp;B</em> <em>Re=\ncord</em> be firmly upheld. =E2=80=9CBoth Laura DeGrazia and Karen Green ar=\ne fearsome partisans for rigorous scholarship, while at the same time they =\nare congenial, affirmative, and diplomatic. The <em>NYG&amp;B Record </em>i=\ns in extraordinarily capable hands.=E2=80=9D</p>=0A<p>=0A\tTheir first issue=\n of the <em>NYG&amp;B</em> <em>Record</em> will be published in April.=C2=\n=A0 Inquiries about publishing in the <em>NYG&amp;B</em> <em>Record</em> sh=\nould be sent to <a href=3D\"mailto:editor@nygbs.org\">editor@nygbs.org</a></p>=\n=0A<div>=0A\t<strong>Media Contact</strong></div>=0A<div>=0A\tMcKelden Smith,=\n President</div>=0A<div>=0A\tNew York Genealogical and Biographical Society<=\n/div>=0A<div>=0A\t<a href=3D\"mailto:msmith@nygbs.org\">msmith@nygbs.org</a></=\ndiv>=0A<div>=0A\t212-755-8532 x204</div>=0A<p>=0A\t=C2=A0</p>=0A</div></div><=\n/div>  </div>=0A=0A  =0A  =0A</div>=0A  </div>=0A</div>=0A
